ess|website=India Rail Info}}</ref> \n\n==Route and halts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indiarailinfo.com/train/-train-dr-ambedkar-nagar-nagpur-sf-express-12923/1150/8/18|title=12923/Dr. Ambedkar Nagar - Nagpur SF Express - Indore to Nagpur WR/Western Zone - Railway Enquiry|last=M|first=Yash|website=indiarailinfo.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>==\n\nThe important halts of the train are :\n\n* {{rws|Dr. Ambedkar Nagar}}\n* {{rws|Indore Junction}}\n* {{rws|Dewas Junction}}\n* {{rws|Maksi Junction}}\n* {{rws|Shujalpur}}\n* {{rws|Habibganj}}\n* {{rws|Itarsi Junction}}\n* {{rws|Betul}}\n* {{rws|Amla Junction}}\n*[[Multai]]\n*[[Pandhurna]]\n*[[Katol]]\n* {{rws|Nagpur Junction}}\n\n==Schedule==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Train Number !! Station Code !! Departure Station !! Departure Time !! Departure Day !! Arrival Station !! Arrival Time !! Arrival Day \n|-\n| 12923 || INDB || {{rws|Dr. Ambedkar Nagar}} || 20:55 || Tue || {{rws|Nagpur Junction}} || 08:25 || Wed\n|-\n| 12924 || NGP  || {{rws|Nagpur Junction}} || 19:00 || Wed || {{rws|Dr. Ambedkar Nagar}} || 06:35 || Thu\n|}\n\n==Traction==\n\nBoth trains are hauled by a [[Electric Loco Shed, Vadodara|Vadodara Electric Loco Shed]] based [[WAP 5]] or [[WAP 4E]] electric locomotives.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Ahilyanagari Express]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Railways in Central India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dr. Ambedkar Nagar - Nagpur Express}}\n[[Category:Express trains in India]]\n[[Category:Transport in Dr. Ambedkar Nagar]]\n[[Category:Transport in Nagpur]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 2005]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Maharashtra]]\n", "name_user": "Catalyst Kumar", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dr._Ambedkar_Nagar_-_Nagpur_Superfast_Express"}
{"title_page": "Michael Franzese", "text_new": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Michael Franzese\n| image = Michael Franzese PTG Astrup 2009 crop.jpg\n| image_caption = Franzese in 2009\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|5|27}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| other_names = \"The Yuppie Don\"\n| occupation = [[Mobster]] (former), motivational speaker, writer\n| allegiance = [[Colombo crime family]] (former)\n| conviction = [[Racketeering]] [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]], tax conspiracy\n| conviction_penalty = 10 years' imprisonment and ordered to pay over $14 million in [[restitution]] (1986)\n| parents = [[John Franzese]]<br>Cristina Capobianco-Franzese\n| relatives = [[John Franzese Jr.]] (brother)\n| spouse = Camille Garcia (second wife)\n| children = 7\n}}\n\n'''Michael Franzese''' (born May 27, 1951) is an American former New York mobster and [[caporegime]] of the [[Colombo crime family]], and son of former [[underboss]] [[John Franzese]]. Michael Franzese did not intend to participate in organized crime; he enrolled in a [[pre-med]] program at [[Hofstra University]], but dropped out to make money for his family after his father was sentenced to 50 years in prison for bank robbery in 1967. Franzese helped implement a scheme to defraud the federal government out of gasoline taxes in the early 1980s.\n\nBy the age of 35, in 1986, ''[[Fortune Magazine]]'' listed Franzese as number 18 on its list of the \"Fifty Most Wealthy and Powerful Mafia Bosses\". Franzese had claimed that at the height of his career, he was making up to $8 million per week. In 1986, he was sentenced to 10 years in prison on conspiracy charges, released in 1989, rearrested in 1991 for a parole violation, ultimately being released in 1994. While in prison, he became a [[born-again Christian]], and in 1995, he retired to California with his wife and children. Franzese has publicly denounced the life of organized crime and became a [[motivational speaker]] and a writer.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nFranzese was born on May 27, 1951, in the [[Brooklyn]] borough of New York City, to [[John \"Sonny\" Franzese]], a [[Colombo crime family]] [[underboss]], and Cristina Capobianco-Franzese, although it is not entirely certain that Sonny is Michael's biological father.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nysun.com/new-york/godfather-betrayed-by-his-namesake-part-ii/54689/|title=A Godfather Betrayed by His Namesake, Part II|publisher=nysun.com|date=May 17, 2007}}</ref> He later moved to [[Long Island]], which would become home to his countless number of operations. After finishing high school, Franzese entered a [[pre-med]] program at [[Hofstra University]] in 1969; his father originally did not want him to be involved in organized crime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.psu.edu/dept/psforum/Penn_State_Forum/Michael%20Franzese.pdf|title=Penn State Forum Speaker Series Michael Franzese \"Life Choices, Life Stories\"|publisher=psu.edu|date=September 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in 1971, Franzese decided to drop out of college to help his family earn money when his father was sentenced to 50 years in prison for bank robbery in 1967.<ref name=\"newsday.com\">{{cite web|title=At 100, mob underboss Sonny Franzese gets out of federal prison|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/crime/sonny-franzese-released-from-prison-1.13756776|website=Newsday|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> Franzese became acquainted with his father's friends such as [[Joseph Colombo]], and later became inducted as a [[made man]] on Halloween night 1975.<ref name=sunsen>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1992-05-24-9202100205-story.html|title=MEMORIES OF THE MOB, INSIDE AND OUT|publisher=sun-sentinel.com|date=May 24, 1992}}</ref> Franzese took the [[Mafia initiation ritual|blood oath]] alongside best friend Jimmy Angelino, Joseph Peraino Jr., Salvatore Miciotta, Vito Guzzo Sr., and John Minerva - who all died violently over the next twenty years.<ref>{{cite news|title=TWO SLAIN AND ONE HURT IN A MOB-STYLE SHOOTING|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/01/05/nyregion/two-slain-and-one-hurt-in-a-mob-style-shooting.html|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=The New York Times|publisher=Les Ledbetter|date=5 January 1982}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=HOOD'S TALE UNDERLINED IN LEAD|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/hood-tale-underlined-lead-article-1.775529|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=New York Daily News|publisher=William K. Rashbaum|date=16 November 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A mobster's trail of bodies|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/mobster-trail-bodies-article-1.882339|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=New York Daily News|publisher=David Goldiner|date=29 September 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"doj\">[http://newyork.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel08/organizedcrime060408.htm COLOMBO ORGANIZED CRIME FAMILY ACTING BOSS, UNDERBOSS, AND TEN OTHER MEMBERS AND ASSOCIATES INDICTED\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527223611/http://newyork.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel08/organizedcrime060408.htm |date=2010-05-27 }} Department of Justice press release June 4, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Secret|first=Mosi|title=After Serving Six Years, Mobster Receives His Sentence|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/20/nyregion/after-serving-six-years-mobster-receives-his-sentence.html?hp|accessdate=20 March 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 20, 2014}}</ref> Franzese was briefly mentored by Colombo soldier Joseph \"Joe-Joe\" Vitacco (1927-1980).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Born-Again Don|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/1991/02/john-gotti-joe-columbo-fbi-investigation-witness|website=Vanity|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=baseball>{{cite news|last=Schwarz|first=Alan|title=BASEBALL; From Captain to Coach: Ex-Goodfella's New Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/12/sports/baseball-from-captain-to-coach-ex-goodfella-s-new-life.html?src=pm|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 12, 2001}}</ref> \n\nDuring the late 1970s Franzese met with [[Gambino crime family]] boss [[John Gotti]], who was then a soldier. [[Angelo Ruggiero]] was also present. Franzese was contacted by a flea market owner who complained that his partner was using and selling drugs at the market in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn. Franzese agreed to frighten him and become the new partner. Franzese sent Colombo soldier-turned informant Anthony Sarivola and another member who remains unidentified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Even the trial of federal witness Anthony Sarivola bears secrets|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-06-24/news/1991175001_1_airlines-cumberland-anthony-steele|website=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> Gotti however claimed that the scared-off partner was an associate of his. After several meetings, Franzese proposed to buy Gotti out. Gotti replied, \"Buy me out? I buy you out,\" and handed over $70,000. Franzese later expressed admiration for Gotti, citing his strict gangster lifestyle and his overwhelming ego.<ref>{{cite book|title=Blood Covenant|url=https://books.google.com/?id=umj2BgAAQBAJ&pg=PT120&lpg=PT120&dq=john+gotti+blood+covenant#v=onepage&q=john%20gotti%20blood%20covenant&f=false|isbn = 9781603741958|last1 = Franzese|first1 = Michael|date = 2009-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Franzese had become a [[caporegime]] of a crew of 300.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2013/apr/12/former-columbo-family-capo-visit-mob-museum-and-te/|title=Former Colombo family capo to visit Mob Museum and tell how he left the mafia but lived to talk about it|publisher=lasvegassun.com|date=October 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=kfvs/>\n\n== Gasoline bootlegging ==\n\nIn 1980, Franzese was contacted by Lawrence Salvatore Iorizzo, who initially thought of a scheme to defraud the federal government out of gasoline taxes.<ref name=sal>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/20/nyregion/9-linked-to-mafia-are-accused-of-bilking-legitimate-businesses.html|title=9 LINKED TO MAFIA ARE ACCUSED OF BILKING LEGITIMATE BUSINESSES|publisher=nytimes.com|date=December 20, 1985|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524171120/https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/20/nyregion/9-linked-to-mafia-are-accused-of-bilking-legitimate-businesses.html|archive-date=2015-05-24}}</ref> Iorizzo was being hassled by associates of another crime family and promised Franzese a percentage if he would defend and solve the issue. The pair set up 18 stock-bearer companies based in Panama. Once authorities suspected one company of fraudulent activity, Franzese would move onto the next company. Under law at the time in Panama, gasoline could be sold tax-free from one wholesale company to the next.<ref>{{cite news |title= ON THE LAM with an UBER-MOBSTER |url= https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1994/11/14/on-the-lam-with-an-uber-mobster |accessdate= 1 December 2017 |work= The New Yorker |date= November 14, 1994}}</ref> Iorizzo, who later turned informant and testified against Franzese, craved power. As a result of Iorizzo slapping around Shelly Levine over $270,000 debt, Franzese had to cut in Genovese family soldier [[Joseph Galizia|Joseph \"Joe Glitz\" Galizia]] into his operation. He had organized the [[Russian Mafia]] in [[Brighton Beach, Brooklyn]] and both organizations became partners, Franzese sold millions of gallons of gasoline.<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news|title=Former mafia boss Michael Franzese sounds warning over match-fixing|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/5517996/Former-mafia-boss-Michael-Franzese-sounds-warning-over-match-fixing.html|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=2009-06-12|last1=Wilson|first1=Jeremy}}</ref> The family would collect the state and federal taxes, but keep the money instead. At the same time, they were often selling the gas at lower prices than at legitimate gas stations. In 1986, ''[[Fortune Magazine]]'' listed Franzese as number 18 on its list of the \"Fifty Most Wealthy and Powerful Mafia Bosses\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Biggest Mafia Bosses|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1986/11/10/68275/index.htm|work=CNN Money|publisher=Fortune Magazine|accessdate=2011-10-11|author=Roy Rowan|author2=Andrew Kupfer|date=1986-11-10}}</ref> Franzese had claimed that at the height of his career, he was making up to $8 million per week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2014/08/20/mob-boss-calls-a-stock-bubble.html|title=Mob boss calls a stock bubble|publisher=cnbc.com|date=August 20, 2014}}</ref> He bought a home in [[Delray Beach, Florida]].<ref name=sunsen/>\n\n== Entertainment, sports management and other businesses ==\n\nDuring the 1970s, he began to enter the world of legitimate business and by the mid 1980s Franzese had a stronghold on various businesses such as car dealerships, leasing companies, auto repair shops, restaurants, nightclubs, a contractor company, movie production and distribution companies, travel agencies and video stores.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former mobster Michael Franzese is trying to do good in the world as a motivational speaker and author|url=http://business.inquirer.net/180052/business-secrets-of-the-mafia-part-3|website=Business Enquirer|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy 1980, Franzese was a partner with [[booking agent]] Norby Walters in his firm. Franzese's role was to intimidate existing and prospective clients. In 1981, Franzese successfully extorted a role for Walters in the US tour by singer [[Michael Jackson]] and his brothers. In 1982, the manager for singer [[Dionne Warwick]] wanted to drop Walters as an agent; Franzese met with the manager and persuaded him to keep Walters.<ref name=\"link with sports agent\"/>\n\nIn 1983, the FBI launched an investigation into boxing promoter [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King's]] organized crime connections and targeted Franzese to introduce an FBI undercover agent, using the alias Victor Quintana, to King. Franzese, who had never met King, was introduced to him by civil rights leader [[Al Sharpton]]. Franzese first met Sharpton through [[Genovese crime family]] mobster, [[Daniel Pagano]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports of The Times; Is Don King's Asbestos Tuxedo Turning Toxic at Last?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/03/sports/sports-of-the-times-is-don-king-s-asbestos-tuxedo-turning-toxic-at-last.html|accessdate=1 December 2017|agency=The New York Times}}</ref> Sharpton later helped Franzese with muscle as he targeted the security guard unions in Atlantic City. Quintana was to give the impression that he was buying his way into the boxing world in order for King to reveal his criminal associations, however the investigation subsequently collapsed after Quintana failed to follow through with several hundred thousand dollars.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sharpton Says F.B.I. Tape Distorts Truth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/24/nyregion/sharpton-says-fbi-tape-distorts-truth.html|accessdate=1 December 2017|agency=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Walters set up a sports management agency with Franzese as a silent partner. At a meeting he agreed to hand over $50,000 in return for a 25 percent interest from the sports agency.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crime Figure Testifies to Link With Sports Agent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/15/sports/crime-figure-testifies-to-link-with-sports-agent.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=1989-03-15|last1=Fiffer|first1=Steve|last2=Times|first2=Special to The New York}}</ref>\n\n== Indictment and prison ==\n\nIn April 1985, Franzese was acquitted of racketeering charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/20/nyregion/new-breed-said-to-emerge-in-organized-crime.html|title=NEW BREED SAID TO EMERGE IN ORGANIZED CRIME|publisher=nytimes.com|date=December 20, 1985}}</ref> In December 1985, Franzese was one of nine people indicted on 14 counts of racketeering, [[counterfeiting]] and extortion from the gasoline bootlegging racket, and on March 21, 1986, pleaded guilty to one count of racketeering [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] and one count of tax conspiracy.<ref name=sal/><ref name=\"link with sports agent\">{{cite news|last=Fiffer|first=Steve|title=Crime Figure Testifies to Link With Sports Agent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/15/sports/crime-figure-testifies-to-link-with-sports-agent.html?src=pm|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 15, 1989}}</ref><ref name=guilty>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/22/nyregion/franzese-enters-a-plea-of-guilty-to-racketeering.html|title=FRANZESE ENTERS A PLEA OF GUILTY TO RACKETEERING|publisher=nytimes.com|date=March 22, 1986|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524192418/https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/22/nyregion/franzese-enters-a-plea-of-guilty-to-racketeering.html|archive-date=2015-05-24}}</ref> He was sentenced to 10 years in federal prison and ordered to pay over $14 million in [[restitution]], agreeing to sell his mansion in [[Old Brookville, New York]] and use proceeds from the 1986 film he produced, ''[[Knights of the City]]''.<ref name=\"probation violation\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H|title=Mobster Sentenced in Probation Violation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/28/nyregion/mobster-sentenced-in-probation-violation.html?scp=2&sq=%22Michael%20Franzese%22&st=cse|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 28, 1991}}</ref><ref name=guilty/> Franzese had met his future wife Camille Garcia while shooting the film in [[Ft. Lauderdale, Florida]], in 1984.<ref name=sunsen/><ref name=telegraph/>\n\nIn 1989, Franzese was released from prison on parole after serving 43 months.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> On December 27, 1991, Franzese was sentenced in New York to four years in federal prison for violating the [[probation]] requirements from his 1989 release.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> Franzese had been arrested in Los Angeles on a [[tax fraud]] accusation and was sent back to New York for the probation hearing.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> In court, prosecutors complained that Franzese had only started paying the balance of his court-ordered restitution payments earlier that year.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> Franzese was also later subpoenaed to testify at Walters' trial in 1989, as Walters had invoked his name to frighten college athletes into signing management contracts, including [[Maurice Douglass]], allowing him to get a reduced sentence.<ref name=\"link with sports agent\" /><ref name=\"probation violation\"/> Prosecutors have said that Franzese was not considered by the government to be a federal cooperating witness.<ref name=\"probation violation\" /> While imprisoned in 1991, Franzese became a born-again Christian after he was given a [[Bible]] by a prison guard.<ref name=chicago>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2007-09-10-0709100373-story.html|title=Former mobster: 'God changed my heart'|publisher=chicagotribune.com|date=September 10, 2007}}</ref> He also spent time in [[solitary confinement]].<ref name=telegraph/> He was ultimately released on November 7, 1994, retiring from the mob in 1995 by moving to California with his wife and children; the relocation was also a result of receiving multiple death threats and [[contract killing|contracts]] on his life, including one approved by his father.<ref name=kfvs>{{cite news|title=Special Report: Michael Franzese talks about quitting the mob|url=http://www.kfvs12.com/story/12010179/special-report-michael-franzese-talks-about-quitting-the-mob|accessdate=26 November 2017|agency=KFVS|date=2010}}</ref><ref name=baseball/><ref name=telegraph/>\n\n== Motivational speaker and writer ==\n\nIn 1992, Franzese co-authored his first book, an autobiography, ''Quitting the Mob''.<ref>{{cite book |title= Quitting the Mob|url= https://archive.org/details/quittingmobhowyu00fran|url-access= registration|last= Franzese|first= Michael|year= 1992|publisher= [[HarperCollins]]|isbn= 978-0-88368-867-0|last2 = Matera|first2 = Dary|authorlink2= Dary Matera}}</ref> In the book, Franzese discusses his criminal activities, life with his father, and meeting his second wife Camille Garcia.\n\nSince his release in 1994, Franzese has publicly denounced the life of organized crime, and became a [[motivational speaker]] for youth, at schools, and other venues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Saher|title=20 years a mobster, Michael Franzese now inspires gangsters to turn their lives around|url=http://wgntv.com/2017/03/10/former-crime-boss-talks-about-life-after-the-mob-2/|accessdate=April 3, 2017|work=[[WGN-TV]]|date=March 10, 2017}}</ref> He also frequently speaks at Christian conferences and churches, including helping the [[Willow Creek Community Church]], in November 2016, to give each of the 70,000 inmates in the state of Illinois a Christmas package. Franzese also speaks at prisons throughout the world, such as [[HM Prison Pentonville|Pentonville Prison]] in England. In 2016, he vowed to help Christian refugees fleeing the [[Middle East]].<ref>{{cite web|title=In Chicago, former mob boss Michael Franzese vows to help clean up Chicago, organize churches to fight Christian genocide in Syria|url=https://www.prnewschannel.com/2016/11/28/in-chicago-former-mob-boss-michael-franzese-vows-to-help-clean-up-chicago-organize-churches-to-fight-christian-genocide-in-syria/|website=PR News Channel|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFranzese has also been interviewed on several radio, TV and online platforms. On July 23, 2002, while appearing on the HBO television program \"[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]\", Franzese claimed that during the 1970s and 1980s, he persuaded [[New York Yankees]] players who owed money to Colombo loansharks to fix baseball games for betting purposes. The Yankees organization immediately denied Franzese's accusations.<ref name=baseball />\n\nIn 2003, Franzese published ''Blood Covenant'', an updated and expanded life story.<ref>{{cite book |title= Blood Covenant|url= https://archive.org/details/bloodcovenantmic0000fran|url-access= registration|last= Franzese|first= Michael|year= 2003|publisher= [[Whitaker House]]|isbn= 978-0-88368-867-0}}</ref> He appeared in the 2013 ''Inside the American Mob'', a [[National Geographic (U.S. TV channel)|National Geographic]] documentary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Pistone talks about Donnie Brasco on 'Inside the American Mob'|url=https://usedview.com/joe-pistone-talks-about-donnie-brasco-on-inside-the-american-mob/|website=Usedview|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017, Franzese lives in [[Anaheim, California]] and is the father of seven children. As of 2020, he is the author of six books: ''Quitting the Mob'' (1992), ''Blood Covenant'' (2003), ''The Good, the Bad and the Forgiven'' (2009), ''I'll Make You an Offer You Can't Refuse'' (2011), ''From the Godfather to God the Father'' (2014), and ''Blood Covenant: The Story of the \"Mafia Prince\" Who Publicly Quit the Mob and Lived'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Franzese |url=https://www.amazon.com/Michael-Franzese/e/B001KIXYD6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1 |website=Amazon |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\nFranzese was portrayed by Joseph Bono in the [[Martin Scorsese]] film ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990).<ref>{{cite web|title=Former mobster Michael Franzese is trying to do good in the world as a motivational speaker and author|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/former-mobster-michael-franzese-is-trying-to-do-good-in-the-world-as-a-motivational|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=24 February 2018|date=2014-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, a documentary called ''The Definitive Guide To The Mob'' was released by [[Lionsgate]], with Franzese as commentator.<ref>{{cite web |title=The definitive guide to the mob |url=https://lccn.loc.gov/2019600774 |website=Library of Congress |accessdate=15 September 2019 |quote=Originally broadcast on television in 2013.}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the [[National Geographic Channel]] released a six-part series called ''Inside the American Mob'', in which, as among other story lines, Franzese's climb up the ranks in the Colombo family is chronicled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natgeotv.com/me/inside-the-american-mob/about|title=INSIDE THE AMERICAN MOB|publisher=natgeotv.com}}</ref>\n\nHis biopic, ''God the father'', was released in theaters and cinemas across the United States on October 31, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=God the Father |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3722118/releaseinfo?ref_=tt_ql_dt_2 |website=IMDB |accessdate=15 September 2019 |quote=Release Dates USA 31 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, he appeared in a two-part documentary on the American Mafia with television presenter and reporter [[Trevor McDonald]].<ref>[http://www.itv.com/mafiawithtrevor The Mafia with Trevor McDonald<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week13/mafia-trevor-mcdonald The Mafia with Trevor McDonald Episode 1<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He spoke about his wealth, but also the impact of being a member of the Colombo crime family had on his family, and that was why he turned away from organized crime.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11490353/The-Mafia-with-Trevor-McDonald-review.html The Mafia with Trevor McDonald, ITV, review: 'surreal' \u2013 Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailypost.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/trevor-mcdonald-meets-mafia-exposes-8882416 Trevor McDonald Meets the Mafia and exposes shocking tales \u2013 Daily Post<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-mafia-with-trevor-mcdonald-itv-tv-review-nice-guy-trevor-just-isnt-cut-out-for-the-mean-streets-10128802.html The Mafia with Trevor McDonald, review: Nice guy Trevor just isn't cut out for the mean streets | The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nFranzese hosted a stage musical, ''A Mob Story'', at the [[Plaza Hotel & Casino]] in [[Las Vegas]]. The show opened in October 2018 and was created and directed by [[Jeff Kutash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2018/oct/24/a-mob-story-plaza-show-review/|title=The ambitious, original 'A Mob Story' is worth a visit to the Plaza|date=October 24, 2018|publisher=lasvegassun.com}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.michaelfranzese.com|Michael Franzese official website}} \n* {{IMDb name|0291882}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/michaelfranzese YouTube \u2013 Michael Franzese]\n\n{{Colombo crime family}}\n{{American Mafia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franzese, Michael}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombo crime family]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People convicted of racketeering]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:American writers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Organized crime memoirists]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction writers about organized crime in the United States]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Michael Franzese\n| image = Michael Franzese PTG Astrup 2009 crop.jpg\n| image_caption = Franzese in 2009\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|5|27}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| other_names = \"The Yuppie Don\"\n| occupation = [[Mobster]] (former), motivational speaker, writer\n| allegiance = [[Colombo crime family]] (former)\n| conviction = [[Racketeering]] [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]], tax conspiracy\n| conviction_penalty = 10 years' imprisonment and ordered to pay over $14 million in [[restitution]] (1986)\n| parents = [[John Franzese]]<br>Cristina Capobianco-Franzese\n| relatives = [[John Franzese Jr.]] (brother)\n| spouse = Camille Garcia (second wife)\n| children = 7\n}}\n\n'''Michael Franzese''' (born May 27, 1951) is an American former New York mobster and [[caporegime]] of the [[Colombo crime family]], and son of former [[underboss]] [[John Franzese]]. Michael Franzese did not intend to participate in organized crime; he enrolled in a [[pre-med]] program at [[Hofstra University]], but dropped out to make money for his family after his father was sentenced to 50 years in prison for bank robbery in 1967. Franzese helped implement a scheme to defraud the federal government out of gasoline taxes in the early 1980s.\n\nBy the age of 35, in 1986, ''[[Fortune Magazine]]'' listed Franzese as number 18 on its list of the \"Fifty Most Wealthy and Powerful Mafia Bosses\". Franzese had claimed that at the height of his career, he was making up to $8 million per week. In 1986, he was sentenced to 10 years in prison on conspiracy charges, released in 1989, rearrested in 1991 for a parole violation, ultimately being released in 1994. While in prison, he became a [[born-again Christian]], and in 1995, he retired to California with his wife and children. Franzese has publicly denounced the life of organized crime and became a [[motivational speaker]] and a writer.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nFranzese was born on May 27, 1951, in the [[Brooklyn]] borough of New York City, to [[John \"Sonny\" Franzese]], a [[Colombo crime family]] [[underboss]], and Cristina Capobianco-Franzese, although it is not entirely certain that Sonny is Michael's biological father.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nysun.com/new-york/godfather-betrayed-by-his-namesake-part-ii/54689/|title=A Godfather Betrayed by His Namesake, Part II|publisher=nysun.com|date=May 17, 2007}}</ref> He later moved to [[Long Island]], which would become home to his countless number of operations. After finishing high school, Franzese entered a [[pre-med]] program at [[Hofstra University]] in 1969; his father originally did not want him to be involved in organized crime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.psu.edu/dept/psforum/Penn_State_Forum/Michael%20Franzese.pdf|title=Penn State Forum Speaker Series Michael Franzese \"Life Choices, Life Stories\"|publisher=psu.edu|date=September 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in 1971, Franzese decided to drop out of college to help his family earn money when his father was sentenced to 50 years in prison for bank robbery in 1967.<ref name=\"newsday.com\">{{cite web|title=At 100, mob underboss Sonny Franzese gets out of federal prison|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/crime/sonny-franzese-released-from-prison-1.13756776|website=Newsday|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> Franzese became acquainted with his father's friends such as [[Joseph Colombo]], and later became inducted as a [[made man]] on Halloween night 1975.<ref name=sunsen>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1992-05-24-9202100205-story.html|title=MEMORIES OF THE MOB, INSIDE AND OUT|publisher=sun-sentinel.com|date=May 24, 1992}}</ref> Franzese took the [[Mafia initiation ritual|blood oath]] alongside best friend Jimmy Angelino, Joseph Peraino Jr., Salvatore Miciotta, Vito Guzzo Sr., and John Minerva - who all died violently over the next twenty years.<ref>{{cite news|title=TWO SLAIN AND ONE HURT IN A MOB-STYLE SHOOTING|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/01/05/nyregion/two-slain-and-one-hurt-in-a-mob-style-shooting.html|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=The New York Times|publisher=Les Ledbetter|date=5 January 1982}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=HOOD'S TALE UNDERLINED IN LEAD|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/hood-tale-underlined-lead-article-1.775529|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=New York Daily News|publisher=William K. Rashbaum|date=16 November 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A mobster's trail of bodies|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/mobster-trail-bodies-article-1.882339|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=New York Daily News|publisher=David Goldiner|date=29 September 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"doj\">[http://newyork.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel08/organizedcrime060408.htm COLOMBO ORGANIZED CRIME FAMILY ACTING BOSS, UNDERBOSS, AND TEN OTHER MEMBERS AND ASSOCIATES INDICTED\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527223611/http://newyork.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel08/organizedcrime060408.htm |date=2010-05-27 }} Department of Justice press release June 4, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Secret|first=Mosi|title=After Serving Six Years, Mobster Receives His Sentence|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/20/nyregion/after-serving-six-years-mobster-receives-his-sentence.html?hp|accessdate=20 March 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 20, 2014}}</ref> Franzese was briefly mentored by Colombo soldier Joseph \"Joe-Joe\" Vitacco (1927-1980).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Born-Again Don|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/1991/02/john-gotti-joe-columbo-fbi-investigation-witness|website=Vanity|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=baseball>{{cite news|last=Schwarz|first=Alan|title=BASEBALL; From Captain to Coach: Ex-Goodfella's New Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/12/sports/baseball-from-captain-to-coach-ex-goodfella-s-new-life.html?src=pm|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 12, 2001}}</ref> \n\nDuring the late 1970s Franzese met with [[Gambino crime family]] boss [[John Gotti]], who was then a soldier. [[Angelo Ruggiero]] was also present. Franzese was contacted by a flea market owner who complained that his partner was using and selling drugs at the market in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn. Franzese agreed to frighten him and become the new partner. Franzese sent Colombo soldier-turned informant Anthony Sarivola and another member who remains unidentified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Even the trial of federal witness Anthony Sarivola bears secrets|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-06-24/news/1991175001_1_airlines-cumberland-anthony-steele|website=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> Gotti however claimed that the scared-off partner was an associate of his. After several meetings, Franzese proposed to buy Gotti out. Gotti replied, \"Buy me out? I buy you out,\" and handed over $70,000. Franzese later expressed admiration for Gotti, citing his strict gangster lifestyle and his overwhelming ego.<ref>{{cite book|title=Blood Covenant|url=https://books.google.com/?id=umj2BgAAQBAJ&pg=PT120&lpg=PT120&dq=john+gotti+blood+covenant#v=onepage&q=john%20gotti%20blood%20covenant&f=false|isbn = 9781603741958|last1 = Franzese|first1 = Michael|date = 2009-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Franzese had become a [[caporegime]] of a crew of 300.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2013/apr/12/former-columbo-family-capo-visit-mob-museum-and-te/|title=Former Colombo family capo to visit Mob Museum and tell how he left the mafia but lived to talk about it|publisher=lasvegassun.com|date=October 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=kfvs/>\n\n== Gasoline bootlegging ==\n\nIn 1980, Franzese was contacted by Lawrence Salvatore Iorizzo, who initially thought of a scheme to defraud the federal government out of gasoline taxes.<ref name=sal>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/20/nyregion/9-linked-to-mafia-are-accused-of-bilking-legitimate-businesses.html|title=9 LINKED TO MAFIA ARE ACCUSED OF BILKING LEGITIMATE BUSINESSES|publisher=nytimes.com|date=December 20, 1985|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524171120/https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/20/nyregion/9-linked-to-mafia-are-accused-of-bilking-legitimate-businesses.html|archive-date=2015-05-24}}</ref> Iorizzo was being hassled by associates of another crime family and promised Franzese a percentage if he would defend and solve the issue. The pair set up 18 stock-bearer companies based in Panama. Once authorities suspected one company of fraudulent activity, Franzese would move onto the next company. Under law at the time in Panama, gasoline could be sold tax-free from one wholesale company to the next.<ref>{{cite news |title= ON THE LAM with an UBER-MOBSTER |url= https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1994/11/14/on-the-lam-with-an-uber-mobster |accessdate= 1 December 2017 |work= The New Yorker |date= November 14, 1994}}</ref> Iorizzo, who later turned informant and testified against Franzese, craved power. As a result of Iorizzo slapping around Shelly Levine over $270,000 debt, Franzese had to cut in Genovese family soldier [[Joseph Galizia|Joseph \"Joe Glitz\" Galizia]] into his operation. He had organized the [[Russian Mafia]] in [[Brighton Beach, Brooklyn]] and both organizations became partners, Franzese sold millions of gallons of gasoline.<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news|title=Former mafia boss Michael Franzese sounds warning over match-fixing|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/5517996/Former-mafia-boss-Michael-Franzese-sounds-warning-over-match-fixing.html|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=2009-06-12|last1=Wilson|first1=Jeremy}}</ref> The family would collect the state and federal taxes, but keep the money instead. At the same time, they were often selling the gas at lower prices than at legitimate gas stations. In 1986, ''[[Fortune Magazine]]'' listed Franzese as number 18 on its list of the \"Fifty Most Wealthy and Powerful Mafia Bosses\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Biggest Mafia Bosses|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1986/11/10/68275/index.htm|work=CNN Money|publisher=Fortune Magazine|accessdate=2011-10-11|author=Roy Rowan|author2=Andrew Kupfer|date=1986-11-10}}</ref> Franzese had claimed that at the height of his career, he was making up to $8 million per week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2014/08/20/mob-boss-calls-a-stock-bubble.html|title=Mob boss calls a stock bubble|publisher=cnbc.com|date=August 20, 2014}}</ref> He bought a home in [[Delray Beach, Florida]].<ref name=sunsen/>\n\n== Entertainment, sports management and other businesses ==\n\nDuring the 1970s, he began to enter the world of legitimate business and by the mid 1980s Franzese had a stronghold on various businesses such as car dealerships, leasing companies, auto repair shops, restaurants, nightclubs, a contractor company, movie production and distribution companies, travel agencies and video stores.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former mobster Michael Franzese is trying to do good in the world as a motivational speaker and author|url=http://business.inquirer.net/180052/business-secrets-of-the-mafia-part-3|website=Business Enquirer|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy 1980, Franzese was a partner with [[booking agent]] Norby Walters in his firm. Franzese's role was to intimidate existing and prospective clients. In 1981, Franzese successfully extorted a role for Walters in the US tour by singer [[Michael Jackson]] and his brothers. In 1982, the manager for singer [[Dionne Warwick]] wanted to drop Walters as an agent; Franzese met with the manager and persuaded him to keep Walters.<ref name=\"link with sports agent\"/>\n\nIn 1983, the FBI launched an investigation into boxing promoter [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King's]] organized crime connections and targeted Franzese to introduce an FBI undercover agent, using the alias Victor Quintana, to King. Franzese, who had never met King, was introduced to him by civil rights leader [[Al Sharpton]]. Franzese first met Sharpton through [[Genovese crime family]] mobster, [[Daniel Pagano]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports of The Times; Is Don King's Asbestos Tuxedo Turning Toxic at Last?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/03/sports/sports-of-the-times-is-don-king-s-asbestos-tuxedo-turning-toxic-at-last.html|accessdate=1 December 2017|agency=The New York Times}}</ref> Sharpton later helped Franzese with muscle as he targeted the security guard unions in Atlantic City. Quintana was to give the impression that he was buying his way into the boxing world in order for King to reveal his criminal associations, however the investigation subsequently collapsed after Quintana failed to follow through with several hundred thousand dollars.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sharpton Says F.B.I. Tape Distorts Truth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/24/nyregion/sharpton-says-fbi-tape-distorts-truth.html|accessdate=1 December 2017|agency=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Walters set up a sports management agency with Franzese as a silent partner. At a meeting he agreed to hand over $50,000 in return for a 25 percent interest from the sports agency.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crime Figure Testifies to Link With Sports Agent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/15/sports/crime-figure-testifies-to-link-with-sports-agent.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=1989-03-15|last1=Fiffer|first1=Steve|last2=Times|first2=Special to The New York}}</ref>\n\n== Indictment and prison ==\n\nIn April 1985, Franzese was acquitted of racketeering charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/20/nyregion/new-breed-said-to-emerge-in-organized-crime.html|title=NEW BREED SAID TO EMERGE IN ORGANIZED CRIME|publisher=nytimes.com|date=December 20, 1985}}</ref> In December 1985, Franzese was one of nine people indicted on 14 counts of racketeering, [[counterfeiting]] and extortion from the gasoline bootlegging racket, and on March 21, 1986, pleaded guilty to one count of racketeering [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] and one count of tax conspiracy.<ref name=sal/><ref name=\"link with sports agent\">{{cite news|last=Fiffer|first=Steve|title=Crime Figure Testifies to Link With Sports Agent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/15/sports/crime-figure-testifies-to-link-with-sports-agent.html?src=pm|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 15, 1989}}</ref><ref name=guilty>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/22/nyregion/franzese-enters-a-plea-of-guilty-to-racketeering.html|title=FRANZESE ENTERS A PLEA OF GUILTY TO RACKETEERING|publisher=nytimes.com|date=March 22, 1986|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524192418/https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/22/nyregion/franzese-enters-a-plea-of-guilty-to-racketeering.html|archive-date=2015-05-24}}</ref> He was sentenced to 10 years in federal prison and ordered to pay over $14 million in [[restitution]], agreeing to sell his mansion in [[Old Brookville, New York]] and use proceeds from the 1986 film he produced, ''[[Knights of the City]]''.<ref name=\"probation violation\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H|title=Mobster Sentenced in Probation Violation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/28/nyregion/mobster-sentenced-in-probation-violation.html?scp=2&sq=%22Michael%20Franzese%22&st=cse|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 28, 1991}}</ref><ref name=guilty/> Franzese had met his future wife Camille Garcia while shooting the film in [[Ft. Lauderdale, Florida]], in 1984.<ref name=sunsen/><ref name=telegraph/>\n\nIn 1989, Franzese was released from prison on parole after serving 43 months.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> On December 27, 1991, Franzese was sentenced in New York to four years in federal prison for violating the [[probation]] requirements from his 1989 release.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> Franzese had been arrested in Los Angeles on a [[tax fraud]] accusation and was sent back to New York for the probation hearing.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> In court, prosecutors complained that Franzese had only started paying the balance of his court-ordered restitution payments earlier that year.<ref name=\"probation violation\"/> Franzese was also later subpoenaed to testify at Walters' trial in 1989, as Walters had invoked his name to frighten college athletes into signing management contracts, including [[Maurice Douglass]], allowing him to get a reduced sentence.<ref name=\"link with sports agent\" /><ref name=\"probation violation\"/> Prosecutors have said that Franzese was not considered by the government to be a federal cooperating witness.<ref name=\"probation violation\" /> While imprisoned in 1991, Franzese became a born-again Christian after he was given a [[Bible]] by a prison guard.<ref name=chicago>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2007-09-10-0709100373-story.html|title=Former mobster: 'God changed my heart'|publisher=chicagotribune.com|date=September 10, 2007}}</ref> He also spent time in [[solitary confinement]].<ref name=telegraph/> He was ultimately released on November 7, 1994, retiring from the mob in 1995 by moving to California with his wife and children; the relocation was also a result of receiving multiple death threats and [[contract killing|contracts]] on his life, including one approved by his father.<ref name=kfvs>{{cite news|title=Special Report: Michael Franzese talks about quitting the mob|url=http://www.kfvs12.com/story/12010179/special-report-michael-franzese-talks-about-quitting-the-mob|accessdate=26 November 2017|agency=KFVS|date=2010}}</ref><ref name=baseball/><ref name=telegraph/>\n\n== Motivational speaker and writer ==\n\nIn 1992, Franzese co-authored his first book, an autobiography, ''Quitting the Mob''.<ref>{{cite book |title= Quitting the Mob|url= https://archive.org/details/quittingmobhowyu00fran|url-access= registration|last= Franzese|first= Michael|year= 1992|publisher= [[HarperCollins]]|isbn= 978-0-88368-867-0|last2 = Matera|first2 = Dary|authorlink2= Dary Matera}}</ref> In the book, Franzese discusses his criminal activities, life with his father, and meeting his second wife Camille Garcia.\n\nSince his release in 1994, Franzese has publicly denounced the life of organized crime, and became a [[motivational speaker]] for youth, at schools, and other venues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Saher|title=20 years a mobster, Michael Franzese now inspires gangsters to turn their lives around|url=http://wgntv.com/2017/03/10/former-crime-boss-talks-about-life-after-the-mob-2/|accessdate=April 3, 2017|work=[[WGN-TV]]|date=March 10, 2017}}</ref> He also frequently speaks at Christian conferences and churches, including helping the [[Willow Creek Community Church]], in November 2016, to give each of the 70,000 inmates in the state of Illinois a Christmas package. Franzese also speaks at prisons throughout the world, such as [[HM Prison Pentonville|Pentonville Prison]] in England. In 2016, he vowed to help Christian refugees fleeing the [[Middle East]].<ref>{{cite web|title=In Chicago, former mob boss Michael Franzese vows to help clean up Chicago, organize churches to fight Christian genocide in Syria|url=https://www.prnewschannel.com/2016/11/28/in-chicago-former-mob-boss-michael-franzese-vows-to-help-clean-up-chicago-organize-churches-to-fight-christian-genocide-in-syria/|website=PR News Channel|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFranzese has also been interviewed on several radio, TV and online platforms. On July 23, 2002, while appearing on the HBO television program \"[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]\", Franzese claimed that during the 1970s and 1980s, he persuaded [[New York Yankees]] players who owed money to Colombo loansharks to fix baseball games for betting purposes. The Yankees organization immediately denied Franzese's accusations.<ref name=baseball />\n\nIn 2003, Franzese published ''Blood Covenant'', an updated and expanded life story.<ref>{{cite book |title= Blood Covenant|url= https://archive.org/details/bloodcovenantmic0000fran|url-access= registration|last= Franzese|first= Michael|year= 2003|publisher= [[Whitaker House]]|isbn= 978-0-88368-867-0}}</ref> He appeared in the 2013 ''Inside the American Mob'', a [[National Geographic (U.S. TV channel)|National Geographic]] documentary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Pistone talks about Donnie Brasco on 'Inside the American Mob'|url=https://usedview.com/joe-pistone-talks-about-donnie-brasco-on-inside-the-american-mob/|website=Usedview|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017, Franzese lives in [[Anaheim, California]] and is the father of seven children. As of 2020, he is the author of six books: ''Quitting the Mob'' (1992), ''Blood Covenant'' (2003), ''The Good, the Bad and the Forgiven'' (2009), ''I'll Make You an Offer You Can't Refuse'' (2011), ''From the Godfather to God the Father'' (2014), and ''Blood Covenant: The Story of the \"Mafia Prince\" Who Publicly Quit the Mob and Lived'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Franzese |url=https://www.amazon.com/Michael-Franzese/e/B001KIXYD6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1 |website=Amazon |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\nFranzese was portrayed by Joseph Bono in the [[Martin Scorsese]] film ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990).<ref>{{cite web|title=Former mobster Michael Franzese is trying to do good in the world as a motivational speaker and author|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/former-mobster-michael-franzese-is-trying-to-do-good-in-the-world-as-a-motivational|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=24 February 2018|date=2014-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, a documentary called ''The Definitive Guide To The Mob'' was released by [[Lionsgate]], with Franzese as commentator.<ref>{{cite web |title=The definitive guide to the mob |url=https://lccn.loc.gov/2019600774 |website=Library of Congress |accessdate=15 September 2019 |quote=Originally broadcast on television in 2013.}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the [[National Geographic Channel]] released a six-part series called ''Inside the American Mob'', in which, as among other story lines, Franzese's climb up the ranks in the Colombo family is chronicled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natgeotv.com/me/inside-the-american-mob/about|title=INSIDE THE AMERICAN MOB|publisher=natgeotv.com}}</ref>\n\nHis biopic, ''God the father'', was released in theaters and cinemas across the United States on October 31, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=God the Father |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3722118/releaseinfo?ref_=tt_ql_dt_2 |website=IMDB |accessdate=15 September 2019 |quote=Release Dates USA 31 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, he appeared in a two-part documentary on the American Mafia with television presenter and reporter [[Trevor McDonald]].<ref>[http://www.itv.com/mafiawithtrevor The Mafia with Trevor McDonald<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week13/mafia-trevor-mcdonald The Mafia with Trevor McDonald Episode 1<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He spoke about his wealth, but also the impact of being a member of the Colombo crime family had on his family, and that was why he turned away from organized crime.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11490353/The-Mafia-with-Trevor-McDonald-review.html The Mafia with Trevor McDonald, ITV, review: 'surreal' \u2013 Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailypost.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/trevor-mcdonald-meets-mafia-exposes-8882416 Trevor McDonald Meets the Mafia and exposes shocking tales \u2013 Daily Post<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-mafia-with-trevor-mcdonald-itv-tv-review-nice-guy-trevor-just-isnt-cut-out-for-the-mean-streets-10128802.html The Mafia with Trevor McDonald, review: Nice guy Trevor just isn't cut out for the mean streets | The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nFranzese hosted a stage musical, ''A Mob Story'', at the [[Plaza Hotel & Casino]] in [[Las Vegas]]. The show opened in October 2018 and was created and directed by [[Jeff Kutash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2018/oct/24/a-mob-story-plaza-show-review/|title=The ambitious, original 'A Mob Story' is worth a visit to the Plaza|date=October 24, 2018|publisher=lasvegassun.com}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.michaelfranzese.com|Michael Franzese official website}} \n* {{IMDb name|0291882}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/michaelfranzese YouTube \u2013 Michael Franzese]\n\n{{Colombo crime family}}\n{{American Mafia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franzese, Michael}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombo crime family]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People convicted of racketeering]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:American writers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Organized crime memoirists]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction writers about organized crime in the United States]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Franzese"}
{"title_page": "Three Busy Debras", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedy television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Three Busy Debras\n| image                = Three Busy Debras.png\n| image_size           = 250px\n| genre                = [[Comedy]]\n| creator              = \n{{Plainlist|\n* Sandy Honig\n* [[Mitra Jouhari]]\n* Alyssa Stonoha\n}}\n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n{{Plainlist|\n* Sandy Honig\n* Mitra Jouhari\n* Alyssa Stonoha\n}}\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = Anna Dokoza <small>(Pilot)</small>\n| creative_director    = \n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* Sandy Honig\n* Mitra Jouhari\n* Alyssa Stonoha\n}}\n| narrated             = [[Catherine Cohen]]\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 1\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Amy Poehler]]\n* Kim Lessing\n* Sandy Honig\n* Mitra Jouhari\n* Alyssa Stonoha\n* Anna Dokoza\n* Mark Costa{{efn|Mark Costa is executive producer for Alive and Kicking, Inc.}}\n* [[Keith Crofford]]{{efn|name=EPWS|Keith Crofford and Walter Newman are executive producers for Williams Street.}}\n* Walter Newman{{efn|name=EPWS}}\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Jonathan Caso\n* Lacey Leavitt\n* Ingrid Lageder{{efn|Lageder is co-producer.}}\n}}\n| location             = <!-- Nation the series was filmed in, if different from the nation of origin. -->\n| cinematography       = Nathan M. Miller\n| editor               = Jonathan Kramer\n| camera               = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime              = 11 minutes\n| company              = Mail Lizard<br>[[Paper Kite Productions]]<br>[[Cartoon Network Studios|Alive and Kicking, Inc.]]<br>[[Williams Street]]\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[Adult Swim]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080p]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format         = \n| first_run            = <!-- The nation in which the series first aired, if different from country parameter -->\n| released             = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2020|3|29}} \n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = https://www.adultswim.com/videos/three-busy-debras\n}}\n\n'''''Three Busy Debras''''' is an American [[comedy]] television series created, written by, and starring Sandy Honig, [[Mitra Jouhari]], and Alyssa Stonoha. It premiered on [[Cartoon Network]]'s late-night [[Block programming|programming block]], [[Adult Swim]] on March 29, 2020.<ref name=\"deadline-05-18\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|title=Adult Swim Orders Comedy Pilot 'Three Busy Debras' From Amy Poehler|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/adult-swim-comedy-pilot-three-busy-debras-amy-poehler-1202384432/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=13 May 2018|date=8 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"the-hollywood-reporter-05-18\">{{cite web|title=Amy Poehler Comedy Pilot 'Three Busy Debras' Ordered by Adult Swim|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amy-poehler-comedy-pilot-three-busy-debras-ordered-by-adult-swim-1109369|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=13 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"deadline-05-19\"/>\n\n==Premise==\n''Three Busy Debras'' follows \"the surreal day-to-day lives of three deranged housewives, all named Debra, in their affluent suburban town of Lemoncurd, [[Connecticut]].\"<ref name=\"deadline-05-19\"/>\n\n==Cast==\n*Sandy Honig as Debra\n*[[Mitra Jouhari]] as Debra\n*Alyssa Stonoha as Debra\n\n==Development==\nOn May 8, 2018, [[Adult Swim]] announced that it had ordered a [[Television pilot|pilot]] of the show, written by Sandy Honig and directed by Anna Dokoza.<ref name=\"the-hollywood-reporter-05-18\"/> On May 7, 2019, Adult Swim gave the quarter hour [[comedy]] a series order.<ref name=\"deadline-05-19\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Adult Swim Picks Up To Series 'Three Busy Debras' Comedy Produced By Amy Poehler|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/adult-swim-picks-up-series-three-busy-debras-comedy-amy-poehler-1202608157|work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|date=May 7, 2019|accessdate=May 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, 2020, it was announced that the series will premiere on March 29, 2020.<ref name=\"Premiere Date\">{{cite web|title=Hilarious New Series Light Up Sundays on Adult Swim|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/02/12/hilarious-new-series-light-up-sundays-on-adult-swim-935513/20200212adultswim01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=December 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nThe show is produced by [[Amy Poehler]] and Kim Lessing through [[Paper Kite Productions]], Sandy Honig, Mitra Jouhari, Alyssa Stonoha and Anna Dokoza.<ref name=\"deadline-05-18\"/>\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |total_width=70  |background=#FF4FBC |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |writerR=<ref name=\"WGA\">{{cite web |url=https://directories.wga.org/project/1187151/three-busy-debras/ |title=Three Busy Debras |website=[[Writers Guild of America West]] |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=Three Busy Debras \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/three-busy-debras/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>  |country=U.S. |viewers= |episodes= \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = A Very Debra Christmas\n |DirectedBy      = Anna Dokoza<ref name=\"deadline-05-18\"/>\n |WrittenBy       = Sandy Honig, Mitra Jouhari & Alyssa Stonoha\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|29}}\n |Viewers         = 0.525<ref name=\"S0E01ratings\">{{cite web |last1=Metcalf |fir