{"title_page": "Proud Mary", "text_new": "{{About|the song by Creedence Clearwater Revival|the band|Proud Mary (band)|the film|Proud Mary (film)}}\n{{short description|1969 single by Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      = CCR - Proud Mary.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]\n| album      = [[Bayou Country (album)|Bayou Country]]\n| B-side     = [[Born on the Bayou]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1969|01}}<ref name=\"Chronicle\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Chronicle: The 20 Greatest Hits|titlelink=Chronicle, Vol. 1|others=[[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]|year=1991|type=CD booklet|publisher=[[Fantasy Records]]|id=FCD-CCR2-2|location=[[United States|U.S.A.]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Bordowitz, Hank 1998, p. 58\">Bordowitz, Hank. ''Bad moon rising: the unauthorized history of Creedence Clearwater Revival''. Schirmer Books, 1998, p. 58</ref>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" 45 RPM]]\n| recorded   = 1968\n| studio     = [[RCA Records|RCA Studios]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]<ref name=\"Bayou\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921072253/http://www.concordmusicgroup.com/assets/documents01/Artists/Creedence-Clearwater-Revival/FAN-30877-02/Bayou-Country-40th-Anniversary-Liner-Notes.pdf|format=PDF|title=Bayou Country : 40th Anniversary : Liner notes|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n* [[Roots rock]]\n* [[Swamp pop#Swamp rock|swamp rock]]<ref name=\"Phull2008\">{{cite book|author=Hardeep Phull|title=Story Behind the Protest Song: A Reference Guide to the 50 Songs that Changed the 20th Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xiraAAAAMAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=978-0-313-34141-0|page=92}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=07}}\n| label      = [[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]]\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   = [[John Fogerty]]<ref name=\"Chronicle\" />\n| prev_title = [[I Put a Spell on You]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[Bad Moon Rising (song)|Bad Moon Rising]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|5hid10EgMXE|\"Proud Mary\" (lyric video)}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Proud Mary'''\" is a [[Rock music|rock \u2019n\u2019 roll]] song written by [[John Fogerty]] and first recorded by his band [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]].  It was released by [[Fantasy Records]] as a [[Single (music)|single]] from the band's second studio album, ''[[Bayou Country (album)|Bayou Country]]'', which was issued by the same record company in January 1969.  The single is generally considered to have been released in early January 1969,<ref name=\"Chronicle\" /><ref name=\"Bordowitz, Hank 1998, p. 58\" /> although at least one source<ref name=\"Bayou\" /> states that it came out just before Christmas 1968.  The song became a major hit in the United States, peaking at No. 2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in March 1969, the first of five singles to peak at No. 2 for the group.<ref name=\"AMS\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=creedence-clearwater-revival-p3985/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}} |title=Creedence Clearwater Revival \u2013 Billboard Singles |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=November 21, 2010}}</ref> \n\nA cover version by [[Ike and Tina Turner]], released two years later in 1971, did nearly as well, reaching No. 4 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and winning a [[Grammy Award]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn a 1969 interview, Fogerty said that he wrote it in the two days after he was discharged from the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]].<ref name=pc54>{{Pop Chronicles |54| 5|John Fogerty}}</ref>  In the liner notes for the 2008 expanded reissue of ''Bayou Country'', [[Joel Selvin]] explained that the songs for the album started when Fogerty was in the National Guard, that the [[Ostinato|riffs]] for \u201cProud Mary\u201d, \u201c[[Born on the Bayou]]\u201d, and \u201cKeep on Chooglin\u2019\u201d were conceived by Fogerty at a concert in the [[Avalon Ballroom]], and \u201cProud Mary\u201d was arranged from parts of different songs, one of which was about a washerwoman named Mary.<ref name=\"Bayou\" />  The line \"Left a good job in the city\" was written following Fogerty's discharge from the National Guard, and the line \"rollin' on the river\" was from a movie by [[Will Rogers]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Michael Goldberg|editor=Jann S. Wenner| editor-link = Jann Wenner|year=1993|title=Fortunate Son: John Fogerty \u2013 The 1993 Rolling Stone Interview|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=[[United States]]|publisher=Jann S. Wenner|accessdate=December 29, 2010|url=http://riverising.tripod.com/john-interviews/rollingstone2.html}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|\"Proud Mary's\" singer, a low-wage earner, leaves what he considers a \"good job,\" which he might define as steady work, even though for long hours under a dictatorial boss. He decides to follow his impulse and imagination and hitches a ride on a riverboat queen, bidding farewell to the city. Only when the boat pulls out does he see the \"good side of the city\"\u2014which, for him, is one in the distance, far removed from his life. Down by the river and on the boat, the singer finds protection from \"the man\" and salvation from his working-class pains in the nurturing spirit and generosity of simple people who \"are happy to give\" even \"if you have no money.\" The river in Fogerty and traditionally in literature and song is a place holding biblical and epical implications. ... Indeed, the river in \"Proud Mary\" offers not only escape but also rebirth to the singer.<ref>Kitts, Thomas M. (2015). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=8OxzCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22proud+mary%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinsZ_k2fzcAhUSt1MKHbwkAtwQ6AEIRjAG#v=onepage&q=%22proud%20mary%22&f=false John Fogerty: An American Son]'', {{unpaginated}}. Routledge. {{ISBN|9781317961253}}.</ref>}}\n\n{{Quote|The song is a seamless mix of black and [[country music|white]] [[American folk music|roots music]] ...\"Proud Mary\" is, of course, a steamboat traveling up and down the river. Fogerty's lyric sketches out a vivid picture of the protagonist finding a comfortable niche in a community of outsiders ... The story connects back to [[Mark Twain]]; it brings the myth [of \"the rambling man and life along the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]]\"] into the sixties.<ref>Campbell, Michael and Brody, James (2007). ''Rock and Roll: An Introduction'', second edition, p.237-8. Cengage Learning. {{ISBN|9781111794538}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the Macintosh program \"[[GarageBand|Garage Band]]\", Fogerty explained that he liked [[Beethoven's Fifth Symphony]] and wanted to open a song with a similar intro (descending by a third), implying the way \"Proud Mary\" opens with the repeated C chord to A chord. Fogerty wanted to evoke male gospel harmonies, as exemplified by groups he was familiar with such as the [[Swan Silvertones]], the [[Sensational Nightingales]], and the [[Five Blind Boys of Mississippi]]; especially on the line, \"Rollin', rollin', rollin' on the river\"; and in the [[guitar solo]] he did his, \"best [imitation of] [[Steve Cropper]].\"<ref>Fogerty, John (2015). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=PwZ4BgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22proud+mary%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinsZ_k2fzcAhUSt1MKHbwkAtwQ6AEIQDAF#v=onepage&q=%22proud%20mary%22&f=false Fortunate Son: My Life, My Music]'', {{unpaginated}}. Little, Brown. {{ISBN|9780316244565}}.</ref> The basic track for \"Proud Mary\", as with the other songs on the album, was recorded by John Fogerty ([[lead guitar]]), [[Tom Fogerty]] ([[rhythm guitar]]), [[Stu Cook]] ([[Bass guitar|bass]]), and [[Doug Clifford]] ([[Drum kit|drums]]) at [[RCA Records|RCA Studios]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]], with John [[overdubbing]] instruments and all the vocals later.<ref name=\"Bayou\" />\n\n==Chart performance==\n\n\"Proud Mary\" was the only song by CCR to be kept from the No. 1 spot by two songs, first unable to dethrone \"[[Everyday People]]\" by [[Sly and the Family Stone]] and then passed by \"[[Dizzy (Tommy Roe song)|Dizzy]]\" by [[Tommy Roe]].\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1969\u20131970)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Go-Set]])\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n{{singlechart |Austria|1|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n|-\n|Belgium\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|Canada (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6060&type=2&interval=50&PHPSESSID=m89iq841abagb37ld9c0fdc1f3|title=RPM \u2013 Item Display: Top Singles \u2013 Volume 11, No. 3, March 17, 1969|date=March 31, 2004|work=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|format=.Php}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart |Germany|4|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|13|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=December 6, 2018}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Dutch Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.top40.nl/creedence-clearwater-revival/creedence-clearwater-revival-proud-mary_6552|title=Top40: Creedence Clearwater Revival \u2013 Proud Mary|date=November 10, 2004|work=[[Dutch Top 40]]}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search+listener&qartistid=742#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - search listener|website=Flavourofnz.co.nz}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart |Norway|6|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(P-R).html|title=SA Charts 1965 - 1989 Songs P-R|website=South African Rock Lists|accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Sweden\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n{{singlechart |UK|8|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival|date=1969-07-12}}\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref name=\"AMS\" />\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|US ''[[Record World]]'' \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Yugoslavia\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1969/top1969.html|title=Go-Set Australian charts \u2013 Top Records for the Year of 1969|website=Poparchives.com.au}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6104&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display \u2013 RPM \u2013 Library and Archives Canada|website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|56\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1969|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1969.html|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1969.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1969/Top 100 Songs of 1969|website=Musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|-\n|}\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|title=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1971|certyear=2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true |nosales=true|noshipments=true}}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Solomon Burke version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Solomon Burke]]\n| album      = Proud Mary\n| B-side     = [[What Am I Living For]]\n| released   = 1969\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country soul]]\n| length     = 3:26\n| label      = [[Bell Records]]<br /><small>783</small>\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Quote|I know a lot of you folks would like to know what the old Proud Mary is all about. Well, I'd like to tell you about her. She's nothing but a big old boat. You see, my forefathers used to ride the bottoms of her as stokers, cooks, and waiters, and I made a vow that when I grew up I'd take a ride on the old Proud Mary ...|intro}}\n\nIn 1969 [[Solomon Burke]] had a small hit with his cover of the song, which was his second release for Bell and was co-produced by singer [[Tamiko Jones]],<ref name=\"discogs.com\">John S. Wilson, \"CAREER RESUMED BY TAMIKO JONES; Recent Polio Victim Presents Songs at Rainbow Grill\", The ''New York Times'' (January 14, 1971):43; [http://www.discogs.com/Solomon-Burke-Proud-Mary/release/2248690 \"Solomon Burke \u2013 Proud Mary\"]; [http://supersoulsisters.blogspot.com/2009/11/tamiko-jones-collection-1963-1986.html \"Tamiko Jones: The Collection (1963\u20131986)\"] (18 November 2009); [http://www.theage.com.au/national/obituaries/original-soul-man-cared-for-spiritual-and-temporal-needs-right-to-the-grave-20101012-16hq5.html \"Original Soul Man Cared for Spiritual and Temporal Needs Right to the Grave\"], ''The Age'' (October 13, 2010). For more regarding Tamiko Jones, see [http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/tamiko%20jones.html \"Tamiko Jones\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130505101618/http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/Tamiko%20Jones.html |date=2013-05-05 }}</ref> who was being rehabilitated after a bout of [[polio]],<ref>Cordell S. Thompson, \"New York Beat\", ''Jet'' (8 October 1970):63.</ref> and was at the time Burke's fianc\u00e9e and manager. Burke recalls: \"We went to [[Muscle Shoals Sound Studio|Muscle Shoals]] and recorded Proud Mary, which they didn't like at all. They thought it was stupid to record a song Proud Mary, which was already on the charts. I was explaining to them that it was a very big record, but it's a very white record, a pop record. We will redo the record, open up the doors for it to get on the r&b charts and make the black stations to play the record ... It was a Solomon Burke record made in Muscle Shoals. We proved that we can make a hit record without [[Jerry Wexler]] eating sandwiches with us. This record was a hit without anybody's help. Proud Mary was only promoted by Tamiko Jones and myself.\" According to Mark Denning, \"While that may have seemed like a bald-faced bid for pop radio play, in Burke's hands the song became a bracing tale of life in the [[Deep South]] as African-Americans searched for liberation aboard the ship that carried them as slaves and put them to undignified labor serving wealthy whites.\"<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/the-soul-clan/chart-history/418664#/album/solomon-burke/proud-mary/26666/review The Soul Clan Album & Song Chart History]. Billboard.com (1968-07-27). Retrieved on 2011-04-07.</ref>\n\n[[John Fogerty]], the song's composer, was impressed by Burke's version of his song: \"Two thousand miles away this man had crawled right up inside my head to learn what Proud Mary was all about. Sure, it's great when someone sings your song, but when he understands it, you listen like it was the first time.\" \"Reworked as a celebration of black consciousness, his potent mix of gospel and country \u2013 the kind that defined his earlier sides for Atlantic \u2013 and driven by a Southern [[funk]]-like strut, . ... it returned Burke to the US R&B Top 20\",<ref>''Mojo'', Issues 158\u2013161 (EMAP Performance Ltd., 2007).</ref> with the single reaching No. 15 on the R&B charts and No. 45 on the pop charts. According to Burke in a 2002 interview: \"I was in Vegas for sixteen weeks at the [[Sands Hotel]]. I missed this record being a hit, because we weren't there to promote the record, we had no backing. The greatest thing I ever did was tell [[Ike Turner]], \"Hey man, you should get on this record ... I think you and [[Tina Turner|Tina]] could tear this thing up.\"<ref name=r2>Solomon Burke, in James Porter, [http://www.roctober.com/roctober/solomonburke.html \"Songs of Solomon: Solomon Burke Interview\"], ''Roctober'' 33 (2002)</ref> On 24 May 1969 Burke sang his version of \"Proud Mary\" on ''[[American Bandstand]]''.<ref>\"Saturday on Eight\", ''Lewiston Evening Journal'' (May 23, 1969):22</ref><ref>[http://www.tv.com/american-bandstand/the-guess-who--solomon-burke/episode/166270/summary.html?tag=;summary American Bandstand: The Guess Who / Solomon Burke Episode Summary on]. Tv.com. Retrieved on 2011-04-07.</ref><ref>[http://www.sidereel.com/American_Bandstand/season-12/episode-39 Watch American Bandstand Season 12 Episode 39|The Guess Who / Solomon Burke]. SideReel. Retrieved on 2011-04-07.</ref>\n\n==The Checkmates Ltd. Featuring Sonny Charles version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Checkmates, Ltd.]] Featuring [[Sonny Charles]]\n| album      = Proud Mary\n| B-side     = Do You Love Your Baby\n| released   = 1969\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Funk]]/[[Soul music|Soul]], [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 3:30\n| label      = [[A&M Records]]<br /><small>1130X</small>\n| writer     =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n[[Checkmates, Ltd.]] released a cover of Proud Mary Featuring [[Sonny Charles]] in 1969. The song peaked at No. 69 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart on the week of 1 November 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1969-11-01|title=THE HOT 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 1, 1969|accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>  It also reached No. 42 in France.<ref>{{cite web|title= Toutes les Chansons N\u00b0 1 des Ann\u00e9es 70 |publisher= InfoDisc |date=1969-12-06 |accessdate=22 December 2019 |url=http://infodisc.fr/Tubes_Artistes_C.php/Tubes_Artiste_Choisi.php |language= fr}}</ref>\n\n==Ike & Tina Turner version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      = Proud Mary - Ike & Tina Turner.jpg\n| alt        =\n|caption=Picture sleeve (Spain)| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Ike & Tina Turner]]\n| album      = [[Workin' Together]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"[[Funkier Than a Mosquito's Tweeter (song)|Funkier Than a Mosquita's Tweeter]]\" (U.S.)|\"[[Honky Tonk Women]]\" (Intl.)}}\n| released   = 30 January 1971\n| format     = [[45 rpm record|7-inch rpm single]]\n| recorded   = 1970\n| studio     =[[Bolic Sound]] (Inglewood, California)\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Funk rock]]|[[soul music|soul]]|[[roots rock]]|[[progressive rock]]}}\n| length     = 5:00</small><br />3:15 (7\" version)\n| label      = [[Liberty Records]]\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   = [[Ike Turner]]\n| prev_title = [[Workin' Together (song)|Workin' Together]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[Ooh Poo Pah Doo]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      = TinaTurner ProudMary.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tina Turner]]\n| album      = <br />[[What's Love Got to Do with It (album)|What's Love Got to Do with It]]\n| B-side     = [[Disco Inferno#Tina Turner version|Disco Inferno]]\n| released   = November 19, 1993\n| format     = [[Promotional recording]]\n| recorded   = 1993\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[Soul music|soul]]}}\n| length     = 5:27\n| label      = [[Parlophone]]\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Chris Lord-Alge]]|Tina Turner|[[Roger Davies (manager)|Roger Davies]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Why Must We Wait Until Tonight]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[GoldenEye (song)|GoldenEye]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n}}\n\n[[Ike & Tina Turner]] released \"Proud Mary\" on January 30, 1971 as the second single from their 1970 album ''[[Workin' Together]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 23, 1971|title=Spotlight Singles - Top 20 Pop Spotlight|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1971/Billboard%201971-01-23.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=70|via=}}</ref> Their rendition differs greatly from the structure of the original, but is also well-known and has become one of [[Tina Turner]]'s most recognizable [[signature song]]s.\n\nIke wasn't keen on the original version, but the cover of \"Proud Mary\" by the [[Checkmates, Ltd.]] piqued his interest.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/itina00turn|title=I, Tina: My Life Story|last=Turner|first=Tina|last2=Loder|first2=Kurt|publisher=William Morrow and Company|others=|year=1986|isbn=9780670808731|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Ike and Tina's version was substantially rearranged by Ike Turner and [[Soko Richardson]].<ref name=\"pressrelease\">[http://lists.drizzle.com/pipermail/postcard2/20040130/021485.html Soko Richardson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006191201/http://lists.drizzle.com/pipermail/postcard2/20040130/021485.html |date=2007-10-06 }} press release from [http://www.pressnetwork.com/ pressnetwork.com] January 30, 2004</ref><ref name=\"Paiste\">[http://www.paiste.com/news/viewnews.php?newsid=4 Noted Soul Drummer Soko Richardson Dies]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Paiste Cymbals, February 2004</ref> The song started off with a slow, sultry [[soul music|soulful]] tone in which Tina introduced the song and warned the audience that she and the band were gonna start it off \"nice and easy\" as \"we never do nothing nice and easy\" but said they would finish it \"nice and rough\". After the lyrics are first sung softly by the Turners, the song is then turned into a [[funk rock]] vamp with Tina and the Ikettes delivering gospel-influenced vocals.\n\nThe single peaked at No. 4 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart on March 27, 1971, two years after the original by Creedence Clearwater Revival was at its peak. It also reached No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' R&B chart, and earned the duo a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Vocal Performance by a Group]] in 1972.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 25, 1972|title=1971 Grammy Champions|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-03-25.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=6|via=}}</ref>\n\nIke and Tina first performed a version of the song on ''[[Playboy After Dark]]'' on December 3, 1969; episode aired on February 3, 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/hugh-hefner-dead-playboy-after-dark-music-performances/|title=15 Electrifying Musical Performances from Hugh Hefner's Playboy After Dark|last=Runtagh|first=Jordan|date=September 28, 2017|website=People}}</ref> They also performed it on The Ed Sullivan Show on January 11, 1970, and on ''[[Soul Train]]'' on April 22, 1972.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=The Best of Soul Train Live|year=2011|type=booklet|publisher=[[Time Life]]}}</ref> The song became a staple in all of their live shows. Live versions of the song were released on the albums ''Live at Carnegie Hall \u2014 What You Hear Is What You Get'' (1971) and ''Live In Paris'' (1971).\n\nIn the Tina Turner biopic, ''[[What's Love Got to Do with It (film)|What's Love Got to Do with It]]'', the song is performed in a timeline of events in Ike and Tina's career in which the couple are transformed from an opening act to [[The Rolling Stones]] to a major headlining act in the 1970s.\n\nThe song continued to be an essential part of Tina's solo performances. In 1988, a live version was included on the album ''[[Tina Live in Europe]]''. Tina later re-recorded the song in the studio for the biopic's 1993 soundtrack album [[What's Love Got to Do with It (album)|of the same name]]. This track was released as a promotional single issued to radio stations and DJs. Tina's solo performance was later included on her 2004 greatest hits album ''[[All the Best (Tina Turner album)|All the Best]]''. After a contestant's take on the song on ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2010, it entered the UK Singles Chart at No. 62 and fell to No. 121 the next week; it also entered the [[Scottish Singles and Albums Chart|Scottish Singles Chart]] at No. 40. Another live version was released in 2009 on the ''[[Tina Live]]'' album. It was recorded on March 21, 2009 in [[Arnhem]], [[Netherlands]] as part of Turner's [[Tina!: 50th Anniversary Tour|50th Anniversary Tour]]. Tina also performed duets of \"Proud Mary\" with [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Cher]].\n\n===Formats and track listings===\n'''1971 US 7\"'''\n\n# Proud Mary \u2013 3:15\n#[[Funkier Than a Mosquito's Tweeter (song)|Funkier Than A Mosquito's Tweeter]] \u2013 2:40\n\n'''1993 US 7\" and cassette single'''\n\n#\"Proud Mary (Edit Live Version) \u2013 4:32\n#\"[[The Best (song)#Tina Turner version|The Best]]\" (Live) \u2013 5:22\n\n'''1993 US CD single'''\n\n#\"Proud Mary (Edit Live Version) \u2013 4:32\n#\"Proud Mary (Edit) \u2013 4:10\n#\"[[We Don't Need Another Hero (Thunderdome)]]\" (Live) \u2013 4:55\n#\"The Best\" (Live) \u2013 5:22\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n====Weekly charts====\n;Ike and Tina Turner\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1971)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Flanders|16|artist=Ike & Tina Turner|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=October 6, 2015|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|11|chartid=5223|accessdate=October 6, 2015|artist=|song=|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/titel-details-7618|title=Ike & Tina Turner \u2013 Top Titel|language=German|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]]|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 21\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Dutch100|5|artist=Ike & Tina Turner|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=October 6, 2015|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"AMT\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=ike-tina-turner-p5711/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}} |title=Ike & Tina Turner \u2013 Billboard Singles |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=November 21, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US ''Billboard'' Soul Singles]]<ref name=\"AMT\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref name=\"CB\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1971|title= Cash Box Top 100|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Music/Cash-Box/70s/1971/Cash-Box-1971-04-03.pdf|journal=Cash Box|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' Top 60 R&B<ref name=\"CBRnB\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 27, 1971|title= Cash Box Top 60 In R&B Locations|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Music/Cash-Box/70s/1971/Cash-Box-1971-03-27.pdf|journal=Cash Box|volume=|pages=39|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''[[Record World]]'' Singles<ref name=\"RW\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1971|title=The Singles Chart|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/71/RW-1971-04-03.pdf|journal=Record World|volume=|pages=33|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Record World'' R&B Singles<ref name=\"RWRnB\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 17, 1971|title=The R&B Singles Chart|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/71/RW-1971-04-17.pdf|journal=Record World|volume=|pages=58|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1971)\n!scope=\"col\"| Rank\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium (Ultratop 50 Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=1971|title=Jaaroverzichten 1971|publisher=Ultratop|language=Dutch|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 96\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1971&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1971|publisher=Hung Medien|language=Dutch|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 7\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1971/BB-1971-12-25.pdf|title=The Year in Music: 1971|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 25, 1971|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 55\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' Top 100<ref name=\"CBend\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 25, 1971|title=Best Records and Artists of 1971|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/70s/1971/Cash-Box-1971-12-25.pdf|journal=Cash Box|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n| 56\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' Top 100 R&B<ref name=\"CBend\" />\n| 32\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n;Tina Turner solo version\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2010)\n! scope=\"col\"| Rank\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Scotland|40|date=2010-09-26|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|62|artist=Tina Turner|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}\n|}\n\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|title=Proud Mary|artist=ike & Tina Turner|award=Gold|relyear=1971|certyear=1971}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|title=Proud Mary|artist=Tina Turner|award=Silver|relyear=2004|certyear=2017}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==Accolades==\n\"Proud Mary\" placed at No. 155 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s 2004 list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs|title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|date=2004-12-09|website=Rolling Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622142703/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs|archivedate=2008-06-22|accessdate=2008-04-10}}</ref> Both CCR and Ike & Tina Turner's versions of the song received [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]]s, in 1998 and 2003, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#p|title=Grammy Hall of Fame|work=[[Grammy Award]]s|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|location=United States|accessdate=January 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n\"Proud Mary\" has, over the years, been recorded by a number of artists. [[Anthony Armstrong Jones]]' 1969 version reached number 22 on the U.S. country charts. Also in 1969, a version recorded by the [[Checkmates, Ltd.]] and produced by [[Phil Spector]] reached number 30 on the [[U.K. Singles Chart]] and number 69 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>[http://musicvf.com/song.php?title=Proud+Mary+by+Sonny+Charles&id=38488 Checkmates, Ltd., \"Proud Mary\" U.S. chart position] Retrieved January 26, 2016.</ref> In 1970, the song was recorded by [[Leonard Nimoy]], in his album ''[[The New World of Leonard Nimoy]]''.\n\n[[Elvis Presley]] began incorporating \"Proud Mary\" into his live shows in 1970. Presley's version is a full-out rocker and is featured in his 1972 concert film ''[[Elvis on Tour]]'', and on his live albums [[On Stage (Elvis Presley album)|''On Stage'']] (1970) and ''[[As Recorded at Madison Square Garden]]'' (1972).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|creedence-clearwater-revival|proud-mary}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Creedence}}\n{{Ike & Tina Turner}}\n{{Tina Turner singles}}\n\n[[Category:1968 songs]]\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:1993 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Fogerty]]\n[[Category:Creedence Clearwater Revival songs]]\n[[Category:Ike & Tina Turner songs]]\n[[Category:Tina Turner songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Checkmates, Ltd. songs]]\n[[Category:Solomon Burke songs]]\n[[Category:Anthony Armstrong Jones songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by John Fogerty]]\n[[Category:Fantasy Records singles]]\n[[Category:Parlophone singles]]\n[[Category:Liberty Records singles]]\n[[Category:Bell Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Songs about rivers]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Ike Turner]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the song by Creedence Clearwater Revival|the band|Proud Mary (band)|the film|Proud Mary (film)}}\n{{short description|1969 single by Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      = CCR - Proud Mary.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]\n| album      = [[Bayou Country (album)|Bayou Country]]\n| B-side     = [[Born on the Bayou]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1969|01}}<ref name=\"Chronicle\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Chronicle: The 20 Greatest Hits|titlelink=Chronicle, Vol. 1|others=[[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]|year=1991|type=CD booklet|publisher=[[Fantasy Records]]|id=FCD-CCR2-2|location=[[United States|U.S.A.]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Bordowitz, Hank 1998, p. 58\">Bordowitz, Hank. ''Bad moon rising: the unauthorized history of Creedence Clearwater Revival''. Schirmer Books, 1998, p. 58</ref>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" 45 RPM]]\n| recorded   = 1968\n| studio     = [[RCA Records|RCA Studios]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]<ref name=\"Bayou\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921072253/http://www.concordmusicgroup.com/assets/documents01/Artists/Creedence-Clearwater-Revival/FAN-30877-02/Bayou-Country-40th-Anniversary-Liner-Notes.pdf|format=PDF|title=Bayou Country : 40th Anniversary : Liner notes|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n* [[Roots rock]]\n* [[Swamp pop#Swamp rock|swamp rock]]<ref name=\"Phull2008\">{{cite book|author=Hardeep Phull|title=Story Behind the Protest Song: A Reference Guide to the 50 Songs that Changed the 20th Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xiraAAAAMAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=978-0-313-34141-0|page=92}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=07}}\n| label      = [[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]]\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   = [[John Fogerty]]<ref name=\"Chronicle\" />\n| prev_title = [[I Put a Spell on You]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[Bad Moon Rising (song)|Bad Moon Rising]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|5hid10EgMXE|\"Proud Mary\" (lyric video)}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Proud Mary'''\" is a [[Rock music|rock \u2019n\u2019 roll]] song written by [[John Fogerty]] and first recorded by his band [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]].  It was released by [[Fantasy Records]] as a [[Single (music)|single]] from the band's second studio album, ''[[Bayou Country (album)|Bayou Country]]'', which was issued by the same record company in January 1969.  The single is generally considered to have been released in early January 1969,<ref name=\"Chronicle\" /><ref name=\"Bordowitz, Hank 1998, p. 58\" /> although at least one source<ref name=\"Bayou\" /> states that it came out just before Christmas 1968.  The song became a major hit in the United States, peaking at No. 2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in March 1969, the first of five singles to peak at No. 2 for the group.<ref name=\"AMS\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=creedence-clearwater-revival-p3985/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}} |title=Creedence Clearwater Revival \u2013 Billboard Singles |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=November 21, 2010}}</ref> \n\nA cover version by [[Ike and Tina Turner]], released two years later in 1971, did nearly as well, reaching No. 4 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and winning a [[Grammy Award]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn a 1969 interview, Fogerty said that he wrote it in the two days after he was discharged from the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]].<ref name=pc54>{{Pop Chronicles |54| 5|John Fogerty}}</ref>  In the liner notes for the 2008 expanded reissue of ''Bayou Country'', [[Joel Selvin]] explained that the songs for the album started when Fogerty was in the National Guard, that the [[Ostinato|riffs]] for \u201cProud Mary\u201d, \u201c[[Born on the Bayou]]\u201d, and \u201cKeep on Chooglin\u2019\u201d were conceived by Fogerty at a concert in the [[Avalon Ballroom]], and \u201cProud Mary\u201d was arranged from parts of different songs, one of which was about a washerwoman named Mary.<ref name=\"Bayou\" />  The line \"Left a good job in the city\" was written following Fogerty's discharge from the National Guard, and the line \"rollin' on the river\" was from a movie by [[Will Rogers]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Michael Goldberg|editor=Jann S. Wenner| editor-link = Jann Wenner|year=1993|title=Fortunate Son: John Fogerty \u2013 The 1993 Rolling Stone Interview|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=[[United States]]|publisher=Jann S. Wenner|accessdate=December 29, 2010|url=http://riverising.tripod.com/john-interviews/rollingstone2.html}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|\"Proud Mary's\" singer, a low-wage earner, leaves what he considers a \"good job,\" which he might define as steady work, even though for long hours under a dictatorial boss. He decides to follow his impulse and imagination and hitches a ride on a riverboat queen, bidding farewell to the city. Only when the boat pulls out does he see the \"good side of the city\"\u2014which, for him, is one in the distance, far removed from his life. Down by the river and on the boat, the singer finds protection from \"the man\" and salvation from his working-class pains in the nurturing spirit and generosity of simple people who \"are happy to give\" even \"if you have no money.\" The river in Fogerty and traditionally in literature and song is a place holding biblical and epical implications. ... Indeed, the river in \"Proud Mary\" offers not only escape but also rebirth to the singer.<ref>Kitts, Thomas M. (2015). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=8OxzCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22proud+mary%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinsZ_k2fzcAhUSt1MKHbwkAtwQ6AEIRjAG#v=onepage&q=%22proud%20mary%22&f=false John Fogerty: An American Son]'', {{unpaginated}}. Routledge. {{ISBN|9781317961253}}.</ref>}}\n\n{{Quote|The song is a seamless mix of black and [[country music|white]] [[American folk music|roots music]] ...\"Proud Mary\" is, of course, a steamboat traveling up and down the river. Fogerty's lyric sketches out a vivid picture of the protagonist finding a comfortable niche in a community of outsiders ... The story connects back to [[Mark Twain]]; it brings the myth [of \"the rambling man and life along the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]]\"] into the sixties.<ref>Campbell, Michael and Brody, James (2007). ''Rock and Roll: An Introduction'', second edition, p.237-8. Cengage Learning. {{ISBN|9781111794538}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the Macintosh program \"[[GarageBand|Garage Band]]\", Fogerty explained that he liked [[Beethoven's Fifth Symphony]] and wanted to open a song with a similar intro (descending by a third), implying the way \"Proud Mary\" opens with the repeated C chord to A chord. Fogerty wanted to evoke male gospel harmonies, as exemplified by groups he was familiar with such as the [[Swan Silvertones]], the [[Sensational Nightingales]], and the [[Five Blind Boys of Mississippi]]; especially on the line, \"Rollin', rollin', rollin' on the river\"; and in the [[guitar solo]] he did his, \"best [imitation of] [[Steve Cropper]].\"<ref>Fogerty, John (2015). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=PwZ4BgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22proud+mary%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinsZ_k2fzcAhUSt1MKHbwkAtwQ6AEIQDAF#v=onepage&q=%22proud%20mary%22&f=false Fortunate Son: My Life, My Music]'', {{unpaginated}}. Little, Brown. {{ISBN|9780316244565}}.</ref> The basic track for \"Proud Mary\", as with the other songs on the album, was recorded by John Fogerty ([[lead guitar]]), [[Tom Fogerty]] ([[rhythm guitar]]), [[Stu Cook]] ([[Bass guitar|bass]]), and [[Doug Clifford]] ([[Drum kit|drums]]) at [[RCA Records|RCA Studios]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]], with John [[overdubbing]] instruments and all the vocals later.<ref name=\"Bayou\" />\n\n==Chart performance==\n\n\"Proud Mary\" was the only song by CCR to be kept from the No. 1 spot by two songs, first unable to dethrone \"[[Everyday People]]\" by [[Sly and the Family Stone]] and then passed by \"[[Dizzy (Tommy Roe song)|Dizzy]]\" by [[Tommy Roe]].\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1969\u20131970)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Go-Set]])\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n{{singlechart |Austria|1|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n|-\n|Belgium\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|Canada (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6060&type=2&interval=50&PHPSESSID=m89iq841abagb37ld9c0fdc1f3|title=RPM \u2013 Item Display: Top Singles \u2013 Volume 11, No. 3, March 17, 1969|date=March 31, 2004|work=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|format=.Php}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart |Germany|4|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|13|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=December 6, 2018}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Dutch Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.top40.nl/creedence-clearwater-revival/creedence-clearwater-revival-proud-mary_6552|title=Top40: Creedence Clearwater Revival \u2013 Proud Mary|date=November 10, 2004|work=[[Dutch Top 40]]}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search+listener&qartistid=742#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - search listener|website=Flavourofnz.co.nz}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart |Norway|6|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(P-R).html|title=SA Charts 1965 - 1989 Songs P-R|website=South African Rock Lists|accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Sweden\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n{{singlechart |UK|8|song=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival|date=1969-07-12}}\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref name=\"AMS\" />\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|US ''[[Record World]]'' \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Yugoslavia\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1969/top1969.html|title=Go-Set Australian charts \u2013 Top Records for the Year of 1969|website=Poparchives.com.au}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6104&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display \u2013 RPM \u2013 Library and Archives Canada|website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|56\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1969|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1969.html|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1969.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1969/Top 100 Songs of 1969|website=Musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|-\n|}\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|title=Proud Mary|artist=Creedence Clearwater Revival|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1971|certyear=2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true |nosales=true|noshipments=true}}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Solomon Burke version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Solomon Burke]]\n| album      = Proud Mary\n| B-side     = [[What Am I Living For]]\n| released   = 1969\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country soul]]\n| length     = 3:26\n| label      = [[Bell Records]]<br /><small>783</small>\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Quote|I know a lot of you folks would like to know what the old Proud Mary is all about. Well, I'd like to tell you about her. She's nothing but a big old boat. You see, my forefathers used to ride the bottoms of her as stokers, cooks, and waiters, and I made a vow that when I grew up I'd take a ride on the old Proud Mary ...|intro}}\n\nIn 1969 [[Solomon Burke]] had a small hit with his cover of the song, which was his second release for Bell and was co-produced by singer [[Tamiko Jones]],<ref name=\"discogs.com\">John S. Wilson, \"CAREER RESUMED BY TAMIKO JONES; Recent Polio Victim Presents Songs at Rainbow Grill\", The ''New York Times'' (January 14, 1971):43; [http://www.discogs.com/Solomon-Burke-Proud-Mary/release/2248690 \"Solomon Burke \u2013 Proud Mary\"]; [http://supersoulsisters.blogspot.com/2009/11/tamiko-jones-collection-1963-1986.html \"Tamiko Jones: The Collection (1963\u20131986)\"] (18 November 2009); [http://www.theage.com.au/national/obituaries/original-soul-man-cared-for-spiritual-and-temporal-needs-right-to-the-grave-20101012-16hq5.html \"Original Soul Man Cared for Spiritual and Temporal Needs Right to the Grave\"], ''The Age'' (October 13, 2010). For more regarding Tamiko Jones, see [http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/tamiko%20jones.html \"Tamiko Jones\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130505101618/http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/Tamiko%20Jones.html |date=2013-05-05 }}</ref> who was being rehabilitated after a bout of [[polio]],<ref>Cordell S. Thompson, \"New York Beat\", ''Jet'' (8 October 1970):63.</ref> and was at the time Burke's fianc\u00e9e and manager. Burke recalls: \"We went to [[Muscle Shoals Sound Studio|Muscle Shoals]] and recorded Proud Mary, which they didn't like at all. They thought it was stupid to record a song Proud Mary, which was already on the charts. I was explaining to them that it was a very big record, but it's a very white record, a pop record. We will redo the record, open up the doors for it to get on the r&b charts and make the black stations to play the record ... It was a Solomon Burke record made in Muscle Shoals. We proved that we can make a hit record without [[Jerry Wexler]] eating sandwiches with us. This record was a hit without anybody's help. Proud Mary was only promoted by Tamiko Jones and myself.\" According to Mark Denning, \"While that may have seemed like a bald-faced bid for pop radio play, in Burke's hands the song became a bracing tale of life in the [[Deep South]] as African-Americans searched for liberation aboard the ship that carried them as slaves and put them to undignified labor serving wealthy whites.\"<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/the-soul-clan/chart-history/418664#/album/solomon-burke/proud-mary/26666/review The Soul Clan Album & Song Chart History]. Billboard.com (1968-07-27). Retrieved on 2011-04-07.</ref>\n\n[[John Fogerty]], the song's composer, was impressed by Burke's version of his song: \"Two thousand miles away this man had crawled right up inside my head to learn what Proud Mary was all about. Sure, it's great when someone sings your song, but when he understands it, you listen like it was the first time.\" \"Reworked as a celebration of black consciousness, his potent mix of gospel and country \u2013 the kind that defined his earlier sides for Atlantic \u2013 and driven by a Southern [[funk]]-like strut, . ... it returned Burke to the US R&B Top 20\",<ref>''Mojo'', Issues 158\u2013161 (EMAP Performance Ltd., 2007).</ref> with the single reaching No. 15 on the R&B charts and No. 45 on the pop charts. According to Burke in a 2002 interview: \"I was in Vegas for sixteen weeks at the [[Sands Hotel]]. I missed this record being a hit, because we weren't there to promote the record, we had no backing. The greatest thing I ever did was tell [[Ike Turner]], \"Hey man, you should get on this record ... I think you and [[Tina Turner|Tina]] could tear this thing up.\"<ref name=r2>Solomon Burke, in James Porter, [http://www.roctober.com/roctober/solomonburke.html \"Songs of Solomon: Solomon Burke Interview\"], ''Roctober'' 33 (2002)</ref> On 24 May 1969 Burke sang his version of \"Proud Mary\" on ''[[American Bandstand]]''.<ref>\"Saturday on Eight\", ''Lewiston Evening Journal'' (May 23, 1969):22</ref><ref>[http://www.tv.com/american-bandstand/the-guess-who--solomon-burke/episode/166270/summary.html?tag=;summary American Bandstand: The Guess Who / Solomon Burke Episode Summary on]. Tv.com. Retrieved on 2011-04-07.</ref><ref>[http://www.sidereel.com/American_Bandstand/season-12/episode-39 Watch American Bandstand Season 12 Episode 39|The Guess Who / Solomon Burke]. SideReel. Retrieved on 2011-04-07.</ref>\n\n==The Checkmates Ltd. Featuring Sonny Charles version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Checkmates, Ltd.]] Featuring [[Sonny Charles]]\n| album      = Proud Mary\n| B-side     = Do You Love Your Baby\n| released   = 1969\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Funk]]/[[Soul music|Soul]], [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 3:30\n| label      = [[A&M Records]]<br /><small>1130X</small>\n| writer     =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n[[Checkmates, Ltd.]] released a cover of Proud Mary Featuring [[Sonny Charles]] in 1969. The song peaked at No. 69 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart on the week of 1 November 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1969-11-01|title=THE HOT 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 1, 1969|accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>  It also reached No. 42 in France.<ref>{{cite web|title= Toutes les Chansons N\u00b0 1 des Ann\u00e9es 70 |publisher= InfoDisc |date=1969-12-06 |accessdate=22 December 2019 |url=http://infodisc.fr/Tubes_Artistes_C.php/Tubes_Artiste_Choisi.php |language= fr}}</ref>\n\n==Ike & Tina Turner version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      = Proud Mary - Ike & Tina Turner.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Ike & Tina Turner]]\n| album      = [[Workin' Together]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Funkier Than a Mosquita's Tweeter\" (U.S.)|\"[[Honky Tonk Women]]\" (Intl.)}}\n| released   = 30 January 1971\n| format     = [[45 rpm record|7-inch rpm single]]\n| recorded   = October 1970\n| studio     =[[Bolic Sound]] (Inglewood, California)\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Funk rock]]|[[soul music|soul]]|[[roots rock]]|[[progressive rock]]}}\n| length     = 5:00</small><br />3:15 (7\" version)\n| label      = [[Liberty Records]]\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   = [[Ike Turner]]\n| prev_title = [[Workin' Together (song)|Workin' Together]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[Ooh Poo Pah Doo]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Proud Mary\n| cover      = TinaTurner ProudMary.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tina Turner]]\n| album      = <br />[[What's Love Got to Do with It (album)|What's Love Got to Do with It]]\n| B-side     = [[Disco Inferno#Tina Turner version|Disco Inferno]]\n| released   = November 19, 1993\n| format     = [[Promotional recording]]\n| recorded   = 1993\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[Soul music|soul]]}}\n| length     = 5:27\n| label      = [[Parlophone]]\n| writer     = [[John Fogerty]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Chris Lord-Alge]]|Tina Turner|[[Roger Davies (manager)|Roger Davies]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Why Must We Wait Until Tonight]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[GoldenEye (song)|GoldenEye]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n}}\n\n[[Ike & Tina Turner]] released \"Proud Mary\" on January 30, 1971 as the second single from their 1970 album ''[[Workin' Together]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 23, 1971|title=Spotlight Singles - Top 20 Pop Spotlight|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1971/Billboard%201971-01-23.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=70|via=}}</ref> Their rendition differs greatly from the structure of the original, but is also well-known and has become one of [[Tina Turner]]'s most recognizable [[signature song]]s.\n\nIke wasn't keen on the original version, but the cover of \"Proud Mary\" by the [[Checkmates, Ltd.]] piqued his interest.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/itina00turn|title=I, Tina: My Life Story|last=Turner|first=Tina|last2=Loder|first2=Kurt|publisher=William Morrow and Company|others=|year=1986|isbn=9780670808731|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Ike and Tina's version was substantially rearranged by Ike Turner and [[Soko Richardson]].<ref name=\"pressrelease\">[http://lists.drizzle.com/pipermail/postcard2/20040130/021485.html Soko Richardson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006191201/http://lists.drizzle.com/pipermail/postcard2/20040130/021485.html |date=2007-10-06 }} press release from [http://www.pressnetwork.com/ pressnetwork.com] January 30, 2004</ref><ref name=\"Paiste\">[http://www.paiste.com/news/viewnews.php?newsid=4 Noted Soul Drummer Soko Richardson Dies]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Paiste Cymbals, February 2004</ref> The song started off with a slow, sultry [[soul music|soulful]] tone in which Tina introduced the song and warned the audience that she and the band were gonna start it off \"nice and easy\" as \"we never do nothing nice and easy\" but said they would finish it \"nice and rough\". After the lyrics are first sung softly by the Turners, the song is then turned into a [[funk rock]] vamp with Tina and the Ikettes delivering gospel-influenced vocals.\n\nThe single peaked at No. 4 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart on March 27, 1971, two years after the original by Creedence Clearwater Revival was at its peak. It also reached No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' R&B chart, and earned the duo a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Vocal Performance by a Group]] in 1972.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 25, 1972|title=1971 Grammy Champions|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-03-25.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=6|via=}}</ref>\n\nIke and Tina first performed a version of the song on ''[[Playboy After Dark]]'' on December 3, 1969; episode aired on February 3, 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/hugh-hefner-dead-playboy-after-dark-music-performances/|title=15 Electrifying Musical Performances from Hugh Hefner's Playboy After Dark|last=Runtagh|first=Jordan|date=September 28, 2017|website=People}}</ref> They also performed it on The Ed Sullivan Show on January 11, 1970, and on ''[[Soul Train]]'' on April 22, 1972.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=The Best of Soul Train Live|year=2011|type=booklet|publisher=[[Time Life]]}}</ref> The song became a staple in all of their live shows. Live versions of the song were released on the albums ''Live at Carnegie Hall \u2014 What You Hear Is What You Get'' (1971) and ''Live In Paris'' (1971).\n\nIn the Tina Turner biopic, ''[[What's Love Got to Do with It (film)|What's Love Got to Do with It]]'', the song is performed in a timeline of events in Ike and Tina's career in which the couple are transformed from an opening act to [[The Rolling Stones]] to a major headlining act in the 1970s.\n\nThe song continued to be an essential part of Tina's solo performances. In 1988, a live version was included on the album ''[[Tina Live in Europe]]''. Tina later re-recorded the song in the studio for the biopic's 1993 soundtrack album [[What's Love Got to Do with It (album)|of the same name]]. This track was released as a promotional single issued to radio stations and DJs. Tina's solo performance was later included on her 2004 greatest hits album ''[[All the Best (Tina Turner album)|All the Best]]''. After a contestant's take on the song on ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2010, it entered the UK Singles Chart at No. 62 and fell to No. 121 the next week; it also entered the [[Scottish Singles and Albums Chart|Scottish Singles Chart]] at No. 40. Another live version was released in 2009 on the ''[[Tina Live]]'' album. It was recorded on March 21, 2009 in [[Arnhem]], [[Netherlands]] as part of Turner's [[Tina!: 50th Anniversary Tour|50th Anniversary Tour]]. Tina also performed duets of \"Proud Mary\" with [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Cher]].\n\n===Formats and track listings===\n'''1971 US 7\"'''\n\n# Proud Mary \u2013 3:15\n# Funkier Than A Mosquito's Tweeter \u2013 2:40\n\n'''1993 US 7\" and cassette single'''\n\n#\"Proud Mary (Edit Live Version) \u2013 4:32\n#\"[[The Best (song)#Tina Turner version|The Best]]\" (Live) \u2013 5:22\n\n'''1993 US CD single'''\n\n#\"Proud Mary (Edit Live Version) \u2013 4:32\n#\"Proud Mary (Edit) \u2013 4:10\n#\"[[We Don't Need Another Hero (Thunderdome)]]\" (Live) \u2013 4:55\n#\"The Best\" (Live) \u2013 5:22\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n====Weekly charts====\n;Ike and Tina Turner\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1971)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Flanders|16|artist=Ike & Tina Turner|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=October 6, 2015|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|11|chartid=5223|accessdate=October 6, 2015|artist=|song=|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/titel-details-7618|title=Ike & Tina Turner \u2013 Top Titel|language=German|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]]|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 21\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Dutch100|5|artist=Ike & Tina Turner|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=October 6, 2015|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"AMT\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=ike-tina-turner-p5711/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}} |title=Ike & Tina Turner \u2013 Billboard Singles |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=November 21, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US ''Billboard'' Soul Singles]]<ref name=\"AMT\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref name=\"CB\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1971|title= Cash Box Top 100|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Music/Cash-Box/70s/1971/Cash-Box-1971-04-03.pdf|journal=Cash Box|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' Top 60 R&B<ref name=\"CBRnB\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 27, 1971|title= Cash Box Top 60 In R&B Locations|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Music/Cash-Box/70s/1971/Cash-Box-1971-03-27.pdf|journal=Cash Box|volume=|pages=39|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''[[Record World]]'' Singles<ref name=\"RW\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1971|title=The Singles Chart|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/71/RW-1971-04-03.pdf|journal=Record World|volume=|pages=33|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Record World'' R&B Singles<ref name=\"RWRnB\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 17, 1971|title=The R&B Singles Chart|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/71/RW-1971-04-17.pdf|journal=Record World|volume=|pages=58|via=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1971)\n!scope=\"col\"| Rank\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium (Ultratop 50 Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=1971|title=Jaaroverzichten 1971|publisher=Ultratop|language=Dutch|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 96\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1971&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1971|publisher=Hung Medien|language=Dutch|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 7\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1971/BB-1971-12-25.pdf|title=The Year in Music: 1971|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 25, 1971|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| 55\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' Top 100<ref name=\"CBend\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 25, 1971|title=Best Records and Artists of 1971|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/70s/1971/Cash-Box-1971-12-25.pdf|journal=Cash Box|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n| 56\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' Top 100 R&B<ref name=\"CBend\" />\n| 32\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n;Tina Turner solo version\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2010)\n! scope=\"col\"| Rank\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Scotland|40|date=2010-09-26|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|62|artist=Tina Turner|song=Proud Mary|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}\n|}\n\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|title=Proud Mary|artist=ike & Tina Turner|award=Gold|relyear=1971|certyear=1971}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|title=Proud Mary|artist=Tina Turner|award=Silver|relyear=2004|certyear=2017}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==Accolades==\n\"Proud Mary\" placed at No. 155 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s 2004 list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs|title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|date=2004-12-09|website=Rolling Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622142703/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs|archivedate=2008-06-22|accessdate=2008-04-10}}</ref> Both CCR and Ike & Tina Turner's versions of the song received [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]]s, in 1998 and 2003, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#p|title=Grammy Hall of Fame|work=[[Grammy Award]]s|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|location=United States|accessdate=January 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n\"Proud Mary\" has, over the years, been recorded by a number of artists. [[Anthony Armstrong Jones]]' 1969 version reached number 22 on the U.S. country charts. Also in 1969, a version recorded by the [[Checkmates, Ltd.]] and produced by [[Phil Spector]] reached number 30 on the [[U.K. Singles Chart]] and number 69 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>[http://musicvf.com/song.php?title=Proud+Mary+by+Sonny+Charles&id=38488 Checkmates, Ltd., \"Proud Mary\" U.S. chart position] Retrieved January 26, 2016.</ref> In 1970, the song was recorded by [[Leonard Nimoy]], in his album ''[[The New World of Leonard Nimoy]]''.\n\n[[Elvis Presley]] began incorporating \"Proud Mary\" into his live shows in 1970. Presley's version is a full-out rocker and is featured in his 1972 concert film ''[[Elvis on Tour]]'', and on his live albums [[On Stage (Elvis Presley album)|''On Stage'']] (1970) and ''[[As Recorded at Madison Square Garden]]'' (1972).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|creedence-clearwater-revival|proud-mary}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Creedence}}\n{{Ike & Tina Turner}}\n{{Tina Turner singles}}\n\n[[Category:1968 songs]]\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:1993 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Fogerty]]\n[[Category:Creedence Clearwater Revival songs]]\n[[Category:Ike & Tina Turner songs]]\n[[Category:Tina Turner songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Checkmates, Ltd. songs]]\n[[Category:Solomon Burke songs]]\n[[Category:Anthony Armstrong Jones songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by John Fogerty]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Fantasy Records singles]]\n[[Category:Parlophone singles]]\n[[Category:Liberty Records singles]]\n[[Category:Bell Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Songs about rivers]]\n", "name_user": "Twixister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIke & Tina Turner version:added links to Funkier Than A Mosquita's Tweeter; added image caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proud_Mary"}
{"title_page": "Naia Izumi", "text_new": "{{Notability|date=February 2020}}\n'''Naia Izumi''' is an American virtuoso guitarist and singer songwriter from [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus, Georgia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Musician-Band/naiaizumiofficial/about/|title=Naia Izumi|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>  residing in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Musician-Band/naiaizumiofficial/about/|title=Naia Izumi|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>. Winner of [[NPR Music]]'s 2018 [[Tiny Desk Concerts#Tiny Desk Contest|Tiny Desk Contest]].<ref name=\"nprmusic\">{{cite web |last1=Shapiro |first1=Ari |title=Meet Naia Izumi, The 2018 Tiny Desk Contest Winner |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/04/24/605005960/meet-naia-izumi-the-2018-tiny-desk-contest-winner |publisher=[[NPR Music]] |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"woub\">{{cite web |title=Los Angeles\u2019 Naia Izumi Wins NPR Music\u2019s 2018 Tiny Desk Contest |url=https://woub.org/2018/04/27/los-angeles-naia-izumi-wins-npr-musics-2018-tiny-desk-contest/ |publisher=[[WOUB-TV|WOUB]] |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"guitarworld\">{{cite web |last1=Varian |first1=Ethan |title=Meet Guitarist Naia Izumi, Winner of NPR's Latest and Greatest Tiny Desk Contest |url=https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/meet-guitarist-naia-izumi-winner-of-nprs-latest-and-greatest-tiny-desk-contest |publisher=[[Guitar World]] |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> .signed to [[Sony Masterworks|SonyMasterworks]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sonymusicmasterworks.com/artist/naia-izumi/|title=Naia Izumi|website=Sony Masterworks|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> in 2019.  Releases include \"[https://open.spotify.com/album/3Cz2GOXIToRq1GO4rNiczp?si=O7IVZ1MaS8uvhmIxn6qyIw Soft spoken]\" 2018<ref>{{Citation|title=Soft Spoken|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/3Cz2GOXIT